0306-how-to-live-without-time","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006372},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers","_id":"5e9820a2f363927515d0cfe4","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Frachel-nuwer-in-karnataka-india"],"bodyIntro":"India has the potential to nearly quadruple the world’s tiger population. But some experts say that that could — ironically — require killing some of them.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBy 11:00, Gopamma Nayaka knew something was wrong. Her husband, Hanumantha, should have returned from collecting firewood an hour before.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGopamma sent for her son, who gathered a search party and headed to Bandipur Tiger Reserve, a nearby national park in south-western India. Just a few metres inside the forest, the group discovered Hanumantha&rsquo;s half-eaten remains. The tiger that killed him was still sitting next to the body.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn the wake of her husband&rsquo;s death, Gopamma struggled not only with grief but economic hardship. Her son had to drop out of university and move back home to support her. &ldquo;My life was much better when my husband was alive,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;My older son could have studied, but now both of my sons have to work. I feel insecure and dependent.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDespite all this, Gopamma feels no resentment toward the tiger that killed her husband. Like many Hindus in India, she views humans as one piece of a complex web of life composed of all creatures, each with an equal right to existence. Nor is she worried that India&rsquo;s tiger population is on the rise. Her husband&rsquo;s death, she says, has nothing to do with the fact that the government is trying to save tigers: &ldquo;This was my fate.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfzn1"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ERural Indians are unique in the world for their high tolerance for co-existing with potentially deadly wildlife. &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t find this in other cultures,&rdquo; says Ullas Karanth, a recently retired carnivore biologist at the Wildlife Conservation Society and a leading expert on tigers. &ldquo;If this kind of thing happened in Montana or Brazil, they&rsquo;d wipe out everything the next day.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20191111-gender-based-violence-prevention-project-in-india\"\u003EThe boys learning anti-sexism in India\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20180926-akashinga-all-women-rangers-in-africa-fighting-poaching\"\u003EMeet the women saving Africa&rsquo;s wildlife\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20171218-what-its-like-living-in-californias-mountain-lion-country\"\u003EWhat it&rsquo;s like living in California&rsquo;s mountain lion county\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003C\u002Ful\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe live-and-let-live outlook has also been foundational for India&rsquo;s transformation into the world&rsquo;s greatest stronghold for tigers. The country holds just 25% of total tiger habitat, but accounts for \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.plos.org\u002Fplosbiology\u002Farticle?id=10.1371\u002Fjournal.pbio.1000485\"\u003E70% of all remaining wild tigers\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, or around 3,000 animals today.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESuccess does not come without cost, however. India&rsquo;s protected areas have not expanded at the same rate as its tiger population, forcing some big cats to turn to human-dominated landscapes for survival. Livestock are killed and sometimes so are people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAttacks are relatively rare, with around \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002F164.100.24.220\u002Floksabhaquestions\u002Fannex\u002F16\u002FAU3952.pdf\"\u003E40 to 50\u003C\u002Fa\u003E people annually killed by tigers &ndash; compared to around 350 people killed each year by elephants. But while getting killed by an elephant is typically viewed as something that just &ldquo;happens&rdquo;, like a car accident, deaths caused by tigers tap into a primordial fear that, if left unresolved, can drive communities to extremes. In many places, traditional tolerance is beginning to fray, leading to riots and targeted killing of tigers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENot every tiger is a man-eater &ndash; not even close. No exact numbers for this behaviour exist, but Karanth guesses that only 10 to 15 of the animals become persistent predators of humans each year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfznt"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"You can’t have everybody in the countryside turning against tigers because of one animal — Ullas Karanth","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen this does happen, though, the most certain way to keep the peace, Karanth and other experts believe, is to quickly dispose of man-eating tigers before they kill again. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the attitude necessary if you want to have a large number of tigers,&rdquo; Karanth says. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t have everybody in the countryside turning against tigers because of one animal.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis is reflected in Indian law, which states that chief wildlife wardens and senior federal officials can issue an order to shoot if it is warranted in the interest of public safety. &ldquo;If a tiger is really a man-eater, we have to go after this man-eating tiger according to a very well-defined standard operating procedure,&rdquo; says Anup Kumar Nayak, additional director general of India&rsquo;s National Tiger Conservation Authority.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut urban animal rights groups &ndash; which hold strong political clout in India &ndash; don&rsquo;t see it that way. No matter how many people a tiger has allegedly killed, many activists argue that man-eaters should be trapped and put into captivity, translocated and re-released, or simply left alone. &ldquo;I feel I am the voice for the voiceless animals,&rdquo; says Jerryl Banait, a physician and leading wildlife activist based in Nagpur. &ldquo;You cannot inflict atrocities and injustices on animals just because they cannot express themselves.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut none of the non-lethal measures Banait and others call for are viable ways of dealing with tigers that stalk and kill humans, Karanth says. Tiger conflicts quickly metastasise into &ldquo;political football&rdquo;, he continues, and while the government waffles under competing pressures, man-eaters go on killing. Local people often eventually enact their own solution, poaching not just the tiger in question, but targeting \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com\u002Fcity\u002Fnagpur\u002Ftigress-two-cubs-poisoned-in-chimur-village\u002Farticleshow\u002F70134603.cms\"\u003Eall the tigers in their area\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. They begin to view India&rsquo;s forest department as the enemy &ndash; and conservation as something opposed to their best interests.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EUnder this scenario, at best, tiger numbers will stagnate. At worst, widespread revenge killings will cause the species to all but disappear.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor India to continue to shine as a tiger success story, Karanth says, it needs to come to terms with the fact that what&rsquo;s best for a species does not always align with what&rsquo;s best for an individual animal &ndash; especially an individual that has taken human lives. In other words, the future of the world&rsquo;s tigers largely depends on convincing Indians to accept that man-eating predators must die in order for the species to thrive. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no other way,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrice of success\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENo one knows how many tigers once roamed India&rsquo;s diverse landscapes, but the cats certainly numbered in the tens, if not hundreds, of thousands. Their decline began centuries ago, with the arrival of shotguns and steel traps. Tigers were targeted for sport by the rich and for bounties by the poor, with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fbooks.google.com\u002Fbooks?id=XFIbjBEQolMC&amp;pg=PA129&amp;lpg=PA129&amp;dq=80,000+tigers+killed+1875+to+1925&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=9JTiAgx2Y4&amp;sig=ACfU3U3xUSZrLQRChu_76eo6NWWB4Tzkpw&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwjlg67L8-TlAhVEi1kKHb4UAMsQ6AEwEHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&amp;q=80%2C000%20tigers%20killed%201875%20to%201925&amp;f=false\"\u003Eone historian\u003C\u002Fa\u003E tallying over 80,000 of the big cats killed from 1875 to 1925. Hunting also wiped out tigers&rsquo; prey, causing the species to be doubly impacted.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfzph"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBy the mid-20th Century, India had lost its Asiatic cheetah and nearly all its Asiatic lions to overhunting. Its tigers would have likely disappeared as well were it not for Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, who outlawed all hunting in 1971. Sometimes referred to as &ldquo;India&rsquo;s greatest wildlife saviour&rdquo;, Gandhi strengthened wildlife legislation, set up protected areas and created a tiger task force.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;This was happening around the time of Rachel Carson and similar environmental movements in Europe &ndash; and the same wave came to India,&rdquo; says Krithi Karanth, chief conservation scientist at the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcwsindia.org\u002F\"\u003ECentre for Wildlife Studies,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E a non-profit organisation in Bangalore, and Ullas Karanth&rsquo;s daughter. &ldquo;People started waking up to the fact that nature&rsquo;s in trouble and that we can&rsquo;t continue business as usual.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfzqw"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Tigers disappeared from 67% of India over a 100-year period","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut tigers didn&rsquo;t immediately rebound. In the 1980s, when Ullas Karanth, now 70, made the switch from a career in engineering to one in conservation, roughly 2,500 tigers still roamed the landscape. Ullas, who has always had a fondness for large predators, decided to focus his career on recovering his country&rsquo;s tiger population. Figuring out how many tigers India had left was a first step. In 1991, he developed a novel, accurate counting method by using camera traps to identify individual tigers&rsquo; unique stripe patterns. He was puzzled, however, when he found that tiger densities varied wildly, from fewer than one to up to 15 tigers per 100 square kilometers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EUllas suspected that low prey densities due to bushmeat poaching could be behind this &ndash; and his hunch proved correct. He eventually confirmed that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcontent\u002F101\u002F14\u002F4854\"\u003Ea single tiger kills around 50 prey animals each year\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, meaning it needs a population of at least 500 prey animals to sustain it. Based on an extensive review of old hunting journals, taxidermy notes and land tenure records, Krithi later estimated that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Froyalsocietypublishing.org\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1098\u002Frspb.2010.0171\"\u003Etigers disappeared from 67% of India\u003C\u002Fa\u003E over a 100-year period, and that many of their prey species, including deer and gaur (the world&rsquo;s largest bovid), likewise declined. &ldquo;The only species that doesn&rsquo;t seem to be in trouble are wild pigs,&rdquo; Krithi says. India&rsquo;s tiger populations, in other words, are held back by the fact that there&rsquo;s not enough to eat.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190118-how-do-you-bring-wildlife-back-to-the-city\"\u003EHow do you bring wildlife back to the city?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20170801-the-animals-thriving-in-the-anthropocene\"\u003EThe animals thriving in the Anthropocene\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20140128-how-wolves-saved-a-famous-park\"\u003EHow reintroducing wolves helped save a famous park\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfzrt"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EStarting in the 1990s, Ullas began pushing for science-based tiger management with a special emphasis on conservation of prey species. He collaborated with others to facilitate the voluntary, government-funded relocation of villages situated within protected areas. When tiger poaching began to surge as a result of growing Chinese demand for the predators&rsquo; parts, Ullas&rsquo;s counting method revealed the severity of the problem, and he worked with officials to develop effective anti-poaching programs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs a result of these and other efforts, tiger populations began to grow. The greater Malenad landscape in southwestern India, for example &ndash; which includes Bandipur Tiger Reserve, where Gopamma&rsquo;s husband was killed &ndash; is now home to 400 tigers, more than four times as many as when Ullas began working there 25 years ago.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs the predator&rsquo;s numbers climb, however, conflicts become inevitable. Competition and territoriality force certain tigers to leave protected areas, especially youngsters seeking to establish their own territories and injured or old animals desperate for food. Most tigers in this situation prey on livestock, but a few wind up killing people as well.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Tigers are normally terrified of humans,&rdquo; Ullas says. &ldquo;But when they discover the vulnerability of people, they suddenly lose that fear and realize these big, tailless monkeys are so easy to catch.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EKilling endangered species sounds counterintuitive, but in the case of habitual man-eaters, Ullas and others believe it is the only option for ensuring conservation of tigers as a species. Like pruning a tree with dead branches, the loss of a few problematic individuals has no negative impact on the whole, they say. Healthy tiger populations experience annual mortalities of 15-20% anyway, and with reproduction rates similar to house cats, deaths are quickly replaced by new births. Because man-eaters are relatively rare, under this system, only a couple dozen or so tigers would need to be put down each year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESome animal activists argue, however, that there are too few tigers left in the wild to justify even one being killed. Others present their case from a moral standpoint. As one \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.scoopwhoop.com\u002Ftwitter-avni-the-tigress\u002F\"\u003ETwitter user in India wrote\u003C\u002Fa\u003E following the death of a man-eating tiger last year: &ldquo;Congratulations people, another tiger murdered, another species closer to extinction.&rdquo; Another lamented: &ldquo;We live in a society where poor animals are killed instead of showing mercy by capturing them.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vfzvr"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBanait believes that tigers definitively proven to be man-eaters &ndash; and with all other options for saving them exhausted &ndash; should be killed. &ldquo;Being a doctor, my first responsibility is to protect human beings,&rdquo; he says. But he sets the bar high for definitively assigning the label of man-eater, such as comparative DNA analyses attributing multiple kills to a particular animal (a single kill, or sporadic kills, he says, could be the result of accidental, chance encounters, not intentional predation). Ullas points out, though, that gathering DNA evidence requires a level of skill that often does not exist in the countryside, and that other forensic and ecological evidence can suffice for pinning kills to a particular tiger. Ultimately, Ullas says, public safety must come first: &ldquo;This is not some OJ Simpson trial, where the tiger must be assumed to be innocent until proven guilty.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIf the government does not provide a timely solution, however, local people will devise their own. They may poison all tigers in their area, or they may \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nytimes.com\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fworld\u002Fasia\u002Ftiger-killing-india.html\"\u003Etrap the cats and beat them to death.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E According to Jose Louies, chief of the wildlife crime control division at the Wildlife Trust of India, professional poachers also take advantage of such situations. Tiger bones, claws, teeth, penises and fur destined for China fetch high prices on the black market, so poachers are happy to take care of problem animals for rural Indians.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Those who lose cattle to tigers, they&rsquo;ll definitely employ poachers,&rdquo; Louies says. &ldquo;Poachers may also pay money to people to keep silent and allow them to take care of the problem and make a profit.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn the worst cases, tiger incidents become release valves for years of economic and social frustrations. Communities turn against conservation efforts and violent mobs form, sometimes incited by timber poachers or other wildlife criminals who hope to weaken the forest department. &ldquo;I fear mobs more than tigers,&rdquo; says AT Poovaihah, a deputy conservator of forests who once ended up in hospital after an encounter with a mob. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s all men, some of whom are drunk, and all of whom are angry. They know we&rsquo;re doing something to capture the animal, but even then, they still want to charge us.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vg02b"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn 2013, for example, Shivamallappa Basappa, a farmer in south-western India, was killed and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-india-25211242\"\u003Epartially eaten by a tiger while grazing his cows\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on the edge of Bandipur Tiger Reserve Karnataka State. He was the third tiger victim in the span of just two weeks, and many people had reached their breaking point. A mob of some 200 men quickly formed. By the time reinforcements arrived at 01:00, the crowd had burned down the local forest department&rsquo;s headquarters and set fire to a government jeep.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We have lived in this place for 60 years, and ever since the beginning, we&rsquo;ve never had a moment of peace from these wild animals,&rdquo; says Shanthamurthy Devappa, a relative of Basappa&rsquo;s, who says he did not take part in the violence himself. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve continually been harassed and bothered by wildlife, and we got angry for that reason. It was the accumulated anger of many years.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E#JusticeForAvni \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EPerhaps no case better epitomises the problems surrounding man-eaters than the story of T-1, a headline-making \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-india-46081484\"\u003Etigress shot in November 2018 after a two-year killing spree\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. By the time T1&rsquo;s dramatic story finally ended, at least 13 people had lost their lives and thousands of others had been terrorised.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vg0hz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn 2015, T-1 began turning up on camera traps in Pandarkhawa in Maharashtra State, a gently undulating landscape of pastures, agricultural fields and forest patches in central India. She preyed on livestock, and soon made her first human kill, a 60-year-old woman found dead in her field with deep slashes in her back. Three months later, T-1 killed a man &ndash; and then another the very next day.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFearing blowback in India&rsquo;s cities, the region&rsquo;s chief wildlife warden issued an order to capture T-1, but not to kill her. India is home to a growing, powerful animal rights movement, &ldquo;an extreme version of Western animal welfarism superimposed on the Hindu ethos&rdquo;, as Ullas characterises it. The movement emerged in the 1990s amidst increasing wealth in urban areas, when &ldquo;300 million people suddenly had more time to think of things other than just making a living&rdquo;, Ullas says.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBanait &ndash; whose love of wildlife was instilled during childhood visits to the countryside with his physician parents &ndash; classifies the movement differently: &ldquo;We are trying our level best to try and put our voices forward to the government so they listen to us. They should provide animals with more safety and with more dignity.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven if authorities do manage to capture a man-eating tiger alive, they then face the question of what to do with it. Relocating it to a different forest only moves the problem. In 2014, for example, officials and amateur naturalists captured a young man-eater near Bhadra Tiger Reserve and released him &ndash; against Ullas&rsquo;s advice &ndash; in a forest some 280km (174 miles) away. Three weeks later, following a streak of livestock attacks, the tiger killed a pregnant woman.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs for keeping captured tigers in captivity, India&rsquo;s zoos are full and other facilities are lacking &ndash; and all promise a dismal existence for a once-wild predator. &ldquo;Any person who knows wildlife and these creatures knows it&rsquo;s such a sad thing to see them in captivity,&rdquo; says Poonam H. Dhanwatey, co-founder of the Tiger Research and Conservation Trust, a non-profit organisation in Maharashtra. &ldquo;What&rsquo;s the quality of life you&rsquo;re giving them, and is it fair to put them in small cages once you remove them from freedom?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"infographic","image":["p07vg0x1"],"imageAlignment":"centre","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-20"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ET-1, however, seemed especially savvy at avoiding capture. She ignored baited traps and evaded search parties deployed into the forest to catch her. After she made her seventh kill &ndash; a 20-year-old man &ndash; communities&rsquo; trust in the government was broken, their patience exhausted. People barred officials from entering their villages or even examining victims&rsquo; bodies, and a mob beat up several forest guards.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EViolence would have likely escalated from there were it not for the efforts of Abharna Maheshwaram, a deputy conservator of forests in the Maharashtra Forest Department. She had a hunch that female officers would be better at keeping the peace than male ones, so she sent 18 of her female colleagues to affected villages wearing civilian clothes. They only revealed their identity as forest guards after earning the trust of the local women. The strategy worked: communities&rsquo; faith in the forest department was restored and they once again began cooperating with officials.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;One thing I learned from T-1 is that whenever there is a human-animal conflict, it is not only about the animal, it&rsquo;s also all about the community with whom you&rsquo;re working,&rdquo; Abharna says. &ldquo;I personally believe that involving communities is the solution for conservation in the country.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGains on the local level were hampered, however, by the ongoing legal, political and social battle that was waging across India&rsquo;s cities over T-1&rsquo;s fate. In February 2018 &ndash; with nine victims now attributed to the man-eating tiger &ndash; the Bombay High Court stayed an order to shoot T-1. Efforts to capture her, including through use of thermal drones, hunting dogs and a paraglider, became increasingly desperate. T-1, meanwhile, became a mother, and her two cubs began joining her on human hunts.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn August, T-1 claimed three human lives in the span of just 24 days. When the government issued a new order to capture her and her cubs and, failing that, to shoot her, Banait sought an intervention through India&rsquo;s Supreme Court. &ldquo;When you&rsquo;re giving capital punishment &ndash; shoot-on-sight for an animal &ndash; there needs to be proper legal justification for these actions,&rdquo; Banait says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-21"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vg1m3"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-22"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ongoing chaos, Ullas says, also contributed to the government&rsquo;s decision to permit Shafath Ali Khan, a private freelance hunter, to take part in T-1&rsquo;s capture. Khan&rsquo;s son, Asghar Ali Khan, who was not permitted to join the hunt, also came along. The Khans are among a dozen wealthy, self-described maharaja who have made careers out of offering sharp-shooting services for high-profile problem animals, Ullas says, but their widely publicised involvement in governmental hunts fuels the flames of outrage among animal welfare advocates and undermines local officials&rsquo; authority. &ldquo;We have 80,000 forest guards, quite a few of whom are excellent marksmen,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;There is absolutely no need for these glory-seeking guys.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOn November 2, Khan&rsquo;s son, Asghar, was finishing dinner when he received a call reporting a tiger sighting on a nearby road. Without informing his father&rsquo;s government counterparts, he and several colleagues grabbed their guns and headed out. From their vehicle they soon spotted T-1, identifiable by a tell-tale &ldquo;trident&rdquo; marking on her side. According to Asghar&rsquo;s widely reported account, one of his colleagues shot the tiger with a tranquiliser dart, causing the enraged cat to charge. Asghar &ndash; allegedly in self-defence, but sitting within his vehicle &ndash; fired on T-1 with a rifle. She died almost instantly.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The hunter always wanted to kill her, and he disrupted the entire operations,&rdquo; Banait says. &ldquo;The process in which they killed Avni was very out of the box, with many irregularities and violations of the law.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ET-1&rsquo;s death sparked very different reactions. In Maharashtra, villagers celebrated with firecrackers; in cities, protestors \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thehindu.com\u002Fnews\u002Fcities\u002Fmumbai\u002Ffile-cases-against-avnis-shooter-panel\u002Farticle26241981.ece\"\u003Eheld candlelight vigils\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Maneka Gandhi, a politician, animal rights activist and widow of Indira Gandhi&rsquo;s son, tweeted to her 200,000 followers that Avni had been &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FManekagandhibjp\u002Fstatus\u002F1058995992496951296?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1058995992496951296&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Findianexpress.com%2Farticle%2Fcities%2Fmumbai%2Fmaneka-gandhi-tigress-t1-avni-devendra-fadnavis-5433581%2F\"\u003Ebrutally murdered\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; and that her killing was &ldquo;patently illegal&rdquo;. She tagged her posts with the widely trending #JusticeForAvni (Gandhi declined an interview request for this story).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-23"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vg252"],"imageAlignment":"left","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-24"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAdvocates soon began accusing the Khans of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thehindu.com\u002Fnews\u002Fcities\u002Fmumbai\u002Ffile-cases-against-avnis-shooter-panel\u002Farticle26241981.ece\"\u003Etampering with evidence\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and questioned whether T-1 had in fact charged the car &ndash; an aberrant behavior for a tiger, which usually reacts to a dart as it would something as minor a bee sting. Forensic analysis of the tiger&rsquo;s wounds later confirmed that she had been shot from the side, likely while crossing the road and certainly not while charging. The tranquilising dart recovered from her thigh also appeared to have been put in place after she was killed. Ultimately, no-one was punished.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ET-1&rsquo;s story made headlines around the world, but as Ullas points out, India has had many tiger cases that are &ldquo;similarly absurd, similarly comic and similarly tragic&rdquo;. The entire fiasco and many of the lives it cost could have been avoided, he says, if the government had simply given the order to shoot to begin with.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom 3,000 to 15,000 \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEliminating man-eaters is the most important factor for retaining social tolerance for tigers, but it&rsquo;s not the only requirement. India also needs to ensure families are quickly compensated for their losses. The government mandates that tiger victims&rsquo; relatives receive 500,000 rupees (around $7,200\u002F&pound;5,580) and that livestock killed by predators are reimbursed as well. But this doesn&rsquo;t always happen.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAfter Gopamma&rsquo;s husband was killed, she says, the junior official she approached for help assured her she would receive compensation. &ldquo;I was naive to have believed him,&rdquo; she says. A higher-up official soon countered that since her husband had been trespassing in the forest when he was killed, she would not be receiving any compensatory funds after all. With no other option, she took out a loan with an exorbitant 60% annual interest rate. &ldquo;I had hoped some compensation would come, but because I&rsquo;m poor, I accepted my fate,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;I felt totally powerless.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-25"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vg274"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-26"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELivestock predation by tigers can also be devastating for a family making just $700 (&pound;542) or so a year, and these impacts are \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fabs\u002Fpii\u002FS0006320717318852\"\u003Emuch more common\u003C\u002Fa\u003E than human deaths. Yet in a survey of 1,370 villages in the Western Ghats, Krithi Karanth found that only \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fabs\u002Fpii\u002FS0006320713002176\"\u003E31% of people who were entitled to compensation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for losses due to human-wildlife conflict were actually getting it. In interviews, she learned that people struggled with confusing paperwork and that they lacked the time or means to make multiple visits the local government office to apply. Some were also deliberately denied or asked to give bribes. &ldquo;There were problems with corruption in the system and with people getting the bureaucratic run-around,&rdquo; Krithi says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn 2015, Krithi and her colleagues at the Centre for Wildlife Studies launched \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcwsindia.org\u002Fwildseve\u002F\"\u003EWildSeve,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E a service that acts as a go-between for people impacted by animals and the government. People call WildSeve&rsquo;s toll free number to report an incident. An inspector soon arrives to document the case using an open-source mobile data kit and takes care of the paperwork. WildSeve now serves half a million people in 600 villages and has filed more than 14,000 cases on their behalf. Processing time for a given claim previously averaged 277 days, but claims are now paid out within 60 days.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWildSeve delivers a host of other services as well, from providing individuals who suffer repeat livestock losses with materials to build tiger-proof sheds, to launching a wildlife education program that reached 3,000 children last year. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a huge optimist,&rdquo; Krithi says. &ldquo;Practical interventions will go a long way to build support for wildlife.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut Krithi&rsquo;s programme, while quickly growing, is for now still confined to a small section of Karnataka. In other parts of the state and country, human-wildlife conflict continues to breed dissatisfaction. People are becoming resistant to the idea of more tigers. Krithi and her father believe there is still time to stop the social tides from changing, however, and to restore tigers to even greater heights &ndash; if only India decides to truly make the species a priority.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBased on the results of government surveys, Ullas calculates that tigers occupy just 10 to 15% of India&rsquo;s 300,000 square kilometres of currently available potential habitat, and over the past 20 years, their numbers have plateaued at about 3,000 individuals. This population trajectory runs contrary to a July press release, in which India&rsquo;s government claimed that the country&rsquo;s tiger population has \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fprojecttiger.nic.in\u002FWriteReadData\u002FPublicationFile\u002FTiger%20Status%20Report_XPS220719032%20%20new%20layout(1).pdf\"\u003Eincreased by 6%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E annually since 2006. &ldquo;In spite of the challenges India faces as a developing country, we have done a wonderful job,&rdquo; says Nayak at the National Tiger Conservation Authority. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s been a steady increase since 2006.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-27"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07vj7qb"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-28"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EUllas, however, calls the methodology behind the findings &ldquo;deeply flawed&rdquo;, and adds that the government has \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thehindu.com\u002Fopinion\u002Fop-ed\u002Fcrouching-tiger-hidden-data\u002Farticle29161305.ece\"\u003Eprevented any outside scientific review\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of its data and analyses for the past 15 years. A paper published in November 2019 in Conservation Science and Practice also concludes that India&rsquo;s tiger monitoring program is &ldquo;unreliable&rdquo;, suffers from &ldquo;a lack of transparency&rdquo; and that its results are &ldquo;not backed by reliable scientific evidence&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENayak counters that the methods are sound, and that &ldquo;a lot of people have been engaged in this process&rdquo;, including three outside experts from the US, UK and Australia &ldquo;who have already examined all the aspects and said that yes, we&rsquo;ve been doing a wonderful job&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EJames Nichols, an emeritus scientist at the United States Geological Survey who specialises in animal population dynamics and management, and who collaborated with Ullas for 25 years to develop tiger sampling methods, agrees that the raw data and methodological details that the government used to arrive at its findings &ldquo;should be published somewhere to permit scrutiny by methodological experts&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESo while &ldquo;India has done far more and far better with tigers than any other country&rdquo;, Ullas says, he believes the picture on the ground is less rosy than politicians would lead the public to believe. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve yet to achieve our full potential.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIndia, he continues, is at a cross-road. It can resign itself to a small, limited number of big cats, or it can become one of the world&rsquo;s most stunning conservation success stories by allowing its tiger population to grow to 10,000 or even 15,000 animals. The country has the money needed to realise this dream, and as ever more people choose to move from the countryside into cities, it also has the space.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor now, however, this is not a governmental goal. &ldquo;I think the [tiger] numbers can increase, but to what extent is very difficult to say at this time,&rdquo; Nayak says. &ldquo;We have 2,900 tigers &ndash; and increasing &ndash; but we still have a lot of difficulties with tigers straying into human-dominated landscapes in certain parts of India and creating a lot of problems.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIndia is one of the world&rsquo;s most biologically diverse nations, but it sets aside less than 5% of its land for wildlife &ndash; compared to the 15% set aside by the US and China. Prakash Javadekar, India&rsquo;s minister of environment, forest and climate change, did not respond to interview requests for this story.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EUllas questions whether the government has the political will to step up its conservation commitments. But while discouraging, he points to India&rsquo;s past as proof that things can quickly and unexpectedly change for the good.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I could have never predicted in the 1970s, when I saw the last tigers shot and paraded, that India would once again have wild tigers,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;These things come in stages. Suddenly something will change, and when it does, we have so many things going in our favour.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E-- \u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EReporting for this story was supported by the Pulitzer Center. \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or\u003Cstrong\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Worklife, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers-29"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-11-21T01:01:01Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The problem with India’s man-eating tigers","headlineShort":"Should man-eating tigers be killed?","image":["p07vj7v6"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e982150f363927515d677c8"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fwildlife"],"summaryLong":"India has the potential to nearly quadruple the world’s tiger population. But some experts say that that could — ironically — require killing some of them.","summaryShort":"Some say it could help save the species","tag":["tag\u002Fenvironment"],"creationDateTime":"2019-11-21T01:00:27.634367Z","entity":"article","guid":"25c6709a-0ea7-4faf-8315-82ffd813a4f0","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers","modifiedDateTime":"2020-01-28T13:06:29.754829Z","project":"future","slug":"20191120-the-problem-of-indias-man-eating-tigers","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006372},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning","_id":"5e9820a4f363927515d0d93b","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Feva-sandoval"],"bodyIntro":"There are many ways of categorising someone’s linguistic skills, but the concept of fluency is hard to define.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMayor Pete Buttigieg&rsquo;s youth, military record, and marital status may distinguish him from the other 2020 US Presidential Election candidates, but it&rsquo;s his rumoured proficiency in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.marieclaire.com\u002Fpolitics\u002Fa27004186\u002Fpete-buttigieg-languages\u002F\"\u003Eseven languages\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that really has people \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-us-canada-47587540\"\u003Etalking\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis seemingly magical feat is especially impressive in predominantly monolingual countries like the United States and the United Kingdom (where, respectively, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.amacad.org\u002Fsites\u002Fdefault\u002Ffiles\u002Facademy\u002Fmultimedia\u002Fpdfs\u002Fpublications\u002Fresearchpapersmonographs\u002FState-of-Languages-in-US.pdf\"\u003Eroughly 80%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fesol.britishcouncil.org\u002Fcontent\u002Flearners\u002Fskills\u002Freading\u002Fbritish-worst-learning-languages\"\u003E62%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of the population speaks only English). But where such enviable talent creates an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theatlantic.com\u002Fhealth\u002Farchive\u002F2019\u002F04\u002Fpete-buttigiegs-polygot-magic\u002F588169\u002F\"\u003Eaura of mystique\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, it also inevitably arouses curiosity. When former US Senator Claire McCaskill asked Buttigieg to comment on his language-speaking ability in a 14 February instalment of MSNBC&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?v=yxH30Nx17H4\"\u003EMorning Joe,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E he replied: &ldquo;it depends what you mean by speak!&rdquo; and added that he can &ldquo;still kind of read a newspaper in Norwegian&hellip; but only slowly&rdquo; and that he has gotten &ldquo;rusty&rdquo; in his Arabic and Dari. That shows humility, but not so much that Buttigieg and his camp definitively dismiss the polyglot rumours.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is not to deride Mayor Buttigieg. His perceived fluency interests me because I&rsquo;m a former language teacher &ndash; having taught English for 11 years in Japan and Italy &ndash; and I am also a Cambridge English exam speaking examiner; a role which requires me to dissect variables in candidates&rsquo; second language production such as pronunciation, discourse management, and grammatical range. Buttigieg is clearly fascinated by languages, willing to learn, and is brave enough to practice with native speakers on television &ndash; qualities that would have made him the star of my classroom. But &ndash; like so many of my ex-students who expected to go from &ldquo;beginner&rdquo; to &ldquo;native&rdquo; proficiency in two months &ndash; Buttigieg may have underestimated what it means to &ldquo;speak&rdquo; a language.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI can relate all too well to overestimating one&rsquo;s own abilities. A &ldquo;heritage speaker&rdquo; of Italian, I&rsquo;d been living in Italy for two years when I overheard a receptionist refer me to me as &ldquo;that foreigner who doesn&rsquo;t speak Italian&rdquo;. I was confused, then gutted. That one casual sentence launched a journey that resulted in my being forced to acknowledge that while I had grown up speaking Italian at home and was \u003Cem\u003Efluent\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, I was not by any means \u003Cem\u003Eproficient\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8rf9"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat does the word &ldquo;fluent&rdquo; actually mean? In lay circles, this term has come to equal \"native-level proficient\", with no grey area between the bumbling beginner and the mellifluous master. An outsider overhearing a conversation in a foreign language only hears a fog of sounds, thus perceiving \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fmashable.com\u002Farticle\u002Fpete-buttigieg-notre-dame-cathedral-french-response\u002F?europe=true\"\u003Eanyone who can cobble together a sentence as &ldquo;fluent&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut Daniel Morgan, head of learning development at the Shenker Institutes of English &ndash; a popular chain of English schools in Italy &ndash; says that \u003Cem\u003Efluency\u003C\u002Fem\u003E actually refers to how &ldquo;smoothly&rdquo; and &ldquo;efficiently&rdquo; a second language (L2) speaker can speak on &ldquo;a range of topics in real time&rdquo;. While fluency may denote a degree of proficiency, it does not automatically imply \u003Cem\u003Eaccuracy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E &ndash; the ability to produce grammatically correct sentences &ndash; nor does it imply grammatical range.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHow important \u003Cem\u003Eare\u003C\u002Fem\u003E accuracy and grammatical range? That depends on the speaker&rsquo;s needs. If they simply wish to converse in social settings, their focus may be solely on achieving fluency, but if the L2 is required for business or academia, accuracy and range are crucial as communications full of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.britishcouncilfoundation.id\u002Fen\u002Fenglish\u002Farticles\u002Ffluency-vs-accuracy\"\u003Eerrors may be seen as unprofessional\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8r5v"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002Ff05e\u002Fe9d0bc97b76e799ebf59e65ef3293ed5f835.pdf\"\u003EThese errors can include\u003C\u002Fa\u003E literal word-for-word translation from their native language (&ldquo;I go in Spain&rdquo;), and language switch (&ldquo;I want eat \u003Cem\u003Eringo\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&rdquo;). Bungled verb tenses, prepositions, plurals, and articles are a natural, even essential, part of the learning process.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life\"\u003EThe man bringing languages back to life \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20181030-the-10-personality-traits-that-english-cant-name\"\u003EThe 10 personality traits that English cannot name \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160811-the-amazing-benefits-of-being-bilingual\"\u003EThe amazing benefits of being bilingual \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany learners, however, fall into the trap of assuming that because they are understood, their speech is &ldquo;perfect&rdquo;. And it isn&rsquo;t only the speaker who glosses over mistakes; in the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fpublication\u002F301296350_Fluency_in_second_language_assessment\"\u003EHandbook of Second Language Assessment,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Nivja de Jong &ndash; senior lecturer at the Leiden University Centre for Linguistics &ndash; argues that grammatical errors usually won&rsquo;t prevent comprehension on the part of the listener, who is automatically able to &ldquo;edit out&rdquo; mistakes. In English, a sentence like &ldquo;I have 17 years&rdquo; is incorrect, yet one nonetheless understands that the speaker wants to say that he is 17 years old. Furthermore, friends and teachers tend to encourage L2 learners rather than discourage them, which may also contribute to inflated self-assessment.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI think of the popular memes comparing how we envision a story or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fi.pinimg.com\u002Foriginals\u002F73\u002F3a\u002F9a\u002F733a9a5311a0f89d3ffa7baffea66bd9.jpg\"\u003Escene in our head\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, to the way we tell it or paint it. Those first crucial years of learning a language, you may be thinking in glorious brush strokes but speaking in scribbles.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8qvs"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESo when can someone say they &ldquo;speak&rdquo; a language? That&rsquo;s the million-dollar question. Can someone consider themselves a Spanish speaker if they&rsquo;re conversational but often can&rsquo;t understand native speakers because they &ldquo;talk too fast&rdquo;? If they use only two verb tenses and every sentence contains mistakes?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe answer may be less &ldquo;yes\u002Fno&rdquo; and more &ldquo;how well?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELuckily, scales for measuring spoken fluency and overall proficiency exist. &ldquo;Fluency is an abstract concept, so we assign observable variables,&rdquo; explains Daniel Morgan. Two of the most reliable factors are &ldquo;speech rate&rdquo; and &ldquo;utterance length&rdquo;. Speech rate can be defined as how much (effective) language you&rsquo;re producing over time, for example how many syllables per minute. Utterance length is, as an average, how much you can produce between disfluencies (e.g. a pause or hesitation). You could look at accuracy as being subsumed into fluency, in terms of grammatical accuracy, lexical choice, pronunciation, and precision.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDe Jong describes the unconscious process any speaker goes through before speaking: conceptualising what to say, formulating how to say it, and, finally, articulating the appropriate sounds. All of this takes place in roughly six syllables per second. A speaker of a second language who needs to convert their thoughts into an unfamiliar language faces an even greater challenge in meeting these strict time constraints. They must also often overcome inhibition and pronunciation challenges. Accuracy may still be lacking at this stage, but make no mistake &ndash; achieving L2 fluency is a colossal feat.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Council of Europe&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.coe.int\u002Fen\u002Fweb\u002Fcommon-european-framework-reference-languages\u002Flevel-descriptions\"\u003ECommon European Framework of References (CEFR) for Languages\u003C\u002Fa\u003E groups language learners into concrete proficiency levels, where fluency and accuracy are just two of many examined criteria. The CEFR &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.coe.int\u002Fen\u002Fweb\u002Fcommon-european-framework-reference-languages\u002Ftable-2-cefr-3.3-common-reference-levels-self-assessment-grid\"\u003Eavailable in 40 languages\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; divides proficiency into six &ldquo;can do&rdquo; levels &ndash; A1, A2, B1, B2, C1, and C2. A corresponds to &ldquo;Basic&rdquo; levels, B to &ldquo;Independent&rdquo;, and C to &ldquo;Proficient.&rdquo; Observable skills include:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA1:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Capabilities range include basic introductions and answering questions about personal details provided the listener speaks slowly and is willing to cooperate.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA2\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can describe in simple terms aspects of his\u002Fher past, environment and matters related to his\u002Fher immediate needs and perform routine tasks requiring basic exchanges of information.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB1:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Can deal with most daily life situations in the country where the language is spoken. Can describe experiences, dreams and ambitions and give brief reasons for opinions and goals.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB2:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Can understand the themes of complex texts on both concrete and abstract topics and will have achieved a degree of fluency and spontaneity, which makes interaction with native speakers possible without significant strain for either party.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can understand a wide range of longer texts and recognise subtleties and implicit meaning; producing clear, well-structured and detailed text on complex subjects, showing controlled use of organisational patterns, connectors and cohesive devices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC2\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can understand virtually everything heard or read, expressing themselves spontaneously, very fluently and precisely, while differentiating finer shades of meaning even in highly complex situations.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGeraint Thomas, a Cambridge English speaking exam team leader, explains: &ldquo;We look at things like cohesion, response rate, discourse management, and pronunciation, but each variable has sub-variables. You can break pronunciation down into \u003Cem\u003Estress\u003C\u002Fem\u003E and \u003Cem\u003Eindividual sounds\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.&rdquo; He emphasises that the progression is gradual. &ldquo;You can expect a good B2 candidate to have certain things under control; the present tense, maybe. However, they might not have their second conditional, and you&rsquo;re aware that this is a progressive thing.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8r18"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThomas adds that individual second language speakers can display different strengths: &ldquo;You can get students who are very accurate but so afraid of making mistakes that their fluency suffers and others who throw themselves into something, who are quite fluent, but their language is full of mistakes.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to research from the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fsupport.cambridgeenglish.org\u002Fhc\u002Fen-gb\u002Farticles\u002F202838506-Guided-learning-hours\"\u003EUniversity of Cambridge English Language Assessment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, it takes 200 guided hours for a motivated learner to advance from one level to the next. Key word, \u003Cem\u003Emotivated\u003C\u002Fem\u003E: language acquisition varies dramatically between individuals. Is the learner open to new structures? Will they build upon what they&rsquo;ve already learned instead of clinging to basic &ldquo;good enough&rdquo; grammar? Will they commit to consistent study and practice? Bottom line: there are many steps between &ldquo;The pen is on the table&rdquo; and penning a perfect thesis on a piece of literature.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProficiency scales provide an excellent gauge for assessing L2 ability, but I believe that the quickest, dirtiest fluency and accuracy &ldquo;tests&rdquo; are real-life situations with native speakers. How smooth and lengthy are your interactions in your L2? Do you avoid or &ldquo;blank&rdquo; at certain topics and situations because you don&rsquo;t have the words? Do you find yourself grasping for &ldquo;key words&rdquo; and content yourself with understanding &ldquo;the sense&rdquo; rather than the entirety of the conversation? How well can you understand a film without subtitles or read a book without a dictionary? If you write an email and ask a native speaker to proofread it, how many errors will they find?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs for me, while my Italian grammatical range has improved dramatically in my nine years in Italy, as a writer I yearn for flawless, native-like accuracy and syntax. I&rsquo;m not there yet, and there are many days where I despair that I never will be.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd then I remind myself that learning a second language is like entering into a marriage. You think you know your partner when you put the ring on their finger, but it&rsquo;s only the beginning, and the commitment is for life. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ieatmypigeon.com\u002F\"\u003EEva Sandoval\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is an Italian-American writer who has been based in Italy since 2010. Her travel, food, and culture writing has appeared in The Telegraph, CNN Travel, Fodor&rsquo;s Travel Guides\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, and HuffPo Travel as well as various luxury hotel and airline magazines. \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Worklife, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-8"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-09-04T00:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"How do we measure language fluency?","headlineShort":"What does being ‘fluent’ really mean?","image":["p07mbx7q"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e982150f363927515d677c8"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Flanguage"],"summaryLong":"There are many ways of categorising someone’s linguistic skills, but the concept of fluency is hard to define.","summaryShort":"There are many ways of measuring someone’s language proficiency","tag":["tag\u002Flanguage"],"creationDateTime":"2019-09-03T15:55:25.944098Z","entity":"article","guid":"65357b2c-6a3d-4547-9f03-f68211327fe0","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:11:31.366112Z","project":"future","slug":"20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006373},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms","_id":"5e9820a3f363927515d0d583","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fjules-montague"],"bodyIntro":"Clinics claim that expensive stem cell therapies can help patients with dementia, autism, multiple sclerosis and even cerebral palsy - and crowdfunding campaigns to pay for the treatments are increasingly common. But are the patients and the donors being misled about the benefits and the risks?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJay Shetty is 8 years old. He is smart and bright, says his mother Shilpa, even if he can&rsquo;t do all the things his younger brother can. &ldquo;Jay doesn&rsquo;t sit up or use his hands much. He&rsquo;s non-verbal and we don&rsquo;t know how well he can see,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But he plays with us and tries to copy everything his younger brother Kairav does.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJay has cerebral palsy. In his early years, Shilpa was desperate to find anything that might help him. Scouring the internet late each night, she read about a stem cell trial at Duke University in North Carolina but Jay wasn&rsquo;t eligible. When Kairav was born in 2015, Shilpa and her husband stored their younger son&rsquo;s umbilical cord blood, which was rich in blood stem cells, hoping another trial would emerge. It did, and this time, children with sibling cord blood could participate. Was she worried about the risks for Jay? &ldquo;It wasn&rsquo;t invasive and it couldn&rsquo;t do any harm really.&rdquo; To raise the &pound;15,000 ($18,200) treatment bill, they supplemented money they had already fundraised for private physiotherapy and hydrotherapy with a personal loan and a further fundraising push supported by the cord bank where Kairav&rsquo;s cord blood had been stored.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerebral palsy is a group of lifelong conditions that affect movement and coordination. In Jay&rsquo;s case, Shilpa explains, there were complications around the time of his birth that led to the condition. There is no cure for cerebral palsy but physiotherapy, speech therapy and occupational therapy can help some symptoms. Shilpa hoped, though, that Jay&rsquo;s stem cell therapy &ndash; a two-hour infusion into his veins &ndash; would bring benefits far beyond everything they had tried before.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1w2g"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWe all have stem cells &ndash; these are building-block cells of sorts, with the ability to develop into a wide range of specialised cell types, such as muscle, skin, or brain cells. Stem cells not only replenish our old cells but also spring into action to repair and replace injured tissue. As a result, they have been likened to our \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fipscell.com\u002Fwhat-are-stem-cells\u002F\"\u003Eown army of microscopic doctors\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, but that army is relatively small.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe excitement around stem cell therapy revolves around the ability to grow more of these cells in the laboratory so they can be used to produce new tissue, replace damaged cells, and unravel disease mechanisms.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20161208-why-vitamin-supplements-could-kill-you\"\u003EWhy vitamin pills may be bad for you \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180306-a-spa-where-patients-bathe-in-radiactive-water\"\u003EA spa where patients bathe in radioactive water \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180203-the-ambitious-quest-to-cure-ageing-like-a-disease\"\u003EThe ambitious quest to cure ageing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo far, researchers have primarily focused on developing two different types of stem cells: embryonic and adult. &nbsp;Embryonic stem cells, which are extracted from a growing embryo, have the natural advantage of being able to give rise to any other cell in the body, an attribute known as pluripotency. But some people have raised ethical concerns about the use of embryos in deriving these stem cells &ndash; issues that are circumvented by the use of stems cells harvested from adult tissues. Adult stem cells are not naturally pluripotent, which means they tend to be more specialised and so only able to develop into a narrower range of cell types. They can be re-programmed, however, to regain that developmental flexibility.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStem cell therapies certainly do hold genuine promise for certain disorders. Proven and licensed stem cell-based treatments already exist for blood and immune conditions such as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.anthonynolan.org\u002Fpatients-and-families\u002Funderstanding-stem-cell-transplants\u002Fwhat-stem-cell-transplant\"\u003Eleukaemia, lymphoma and myeloma\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It is also approved in some countries for \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ema.europa.eu\u002Fen\u002Fnews\u002Ffirst-stem-cell-therapy-recommended-approval-eu\" target=\"_blank\"\u003Echemical burns to the eye\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHopes of using stem cells to treat other disorders have inspired many new clinical trials and driven a &ldquo;stem cell tourism&rdquo;, centred in Ukraine, Panama and Thailand. By 2018, there were \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F29805145\"\u003Eover 432 US-based business at 716 clinics engaged in direct-to-consumer marketing of stem cell treatment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese clinics universally share one feature: eye-watering fees &ndash; and even trials like the one at Duke University have a hefty price tag.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1tjm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThat&rsquo;s where crowdfunding comes into its own. A recent study in the Journal of the American Medical Association identified \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjamanetwork.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fjama\u002Farticle-abstract\u002F2680538?redirect=true\"\u003E408 US campaigns for stem cell treatment on YouCaring and GoFundMe\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, with more than $7m sought and 13,050 donor pledges. The clinics often actively encourage these campaigns: one at Northwestern Medicine has a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ipscell.com\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2016\u002F03\u002FNWstem-cell_handbook.pdf\"\u003Ehandbook\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with a section on &ldquo;soliciting methods&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe campaigns often underplay potential risks or omit them entirely:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It&rsquo;s that simple and quick, and with only minimal side effects,&rdquo; claims one page attempting to raise funds for a man with Parkinson&rsquo;s.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Most importantly it has been shown to slow the disease progression without any side effects,&rdquo; describes another, raising funds for someone with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) &ndash; a common form of motor neurone disease.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnly 26 of those 408 campaigns mentioned &lsquo;risk&rsquo; and even then as risk-free or low-risk compared with alternative treatments.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s understandable that campaigners might underplay the dangers &ndash; donors might not contribute otherwise. But these cases tell another story:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003EIn 2017, Doris Tyler, a 77-year old former music teacher raised money on GoFundMe to cover stem cell treatment in Georgia (US) to treat age-related macular degeneration (ARMD). &ldquo;We love you, Doris!&rdquo; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.healio.com\u002Fophthalmology\u002Fjournals\u002Fosli\u002F2017-9-48-9\u002F%7Be9b7d81e-7400-4991-a540-16176991b1d7%7D\u002Fbilateral-retinal-detachments-after-intravitreal-injection-of-adipose-derived-stem-cells-in-a-patient-with-exudative-macular-degeneration\"\u003Eone supporter wrote\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Before treatment, she was able to read large-print books and navigate her home. Tyler \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.healio.com\u002Fophthalmology\u002Fjournals\u002Fosli\u002F2017-9-48-9\u002F%7Be9b7d81e-7400-4991-a540-16176991b1d7%7D\u002Fbilateral-retinal-detachments-after-intravitreal-injection-of-adipose-derived-stem-cells-in-a-patient-with-exudative-macular-degeneration\"\u003Eis now almost blind\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;When I wake up in the morning \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.washingtonpost.com\u002Fnational\u002Fhealth-science\u002Fmiracle-cures-or-modern-quackery-stem-cell-clinics-multiply-with-heartbreaking-results-for-some-patients\u002F2018\u002F04\u002F29\u002F80cbcee8-26e1-11e8-874b-d517e912f125_story.html?utm_term=.240262dbdda1\"\u003Eone of the hardest things is opening my eyes and seeing that everything is still dark\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. And it&rsquo;s going to be this way until I go to sleep.&rdquo; At least \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fscience\u002F2017\u002Fmar\u002F16\u002Fthree-women-with-eye-disease-blinded-by-unproven-stem-cell-treatment\"\u003Ethree other patients\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with ARMD lost their vision following stem cell treatments in Florida in 2015.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003EAt least \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.washingtonpost.com\u002Fnational\u002Fhealth-science\u002Fmiraculous-stem-cell-therapy-has-sickened-people-in-five-states\u002F2019\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fc04b23a4-3539-11e9-854a-7a14d7fec96a_story.html?noredirect=on&amp;noredirect=on&amp;utm_term=.2fb92225fd18\"\u003E17 patients were hospitalised over the past year\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the US after umbilical cord blood injections. The Centers for Disease Control \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cdc.gov\u002Fmmwr\u002Fvolumes\u002F67\u002Fwr\u002Fmm6750a5.htm\"\u003Econfirmed a series of bacterial infections\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Most of these patients were treated at orthopaedic, chiropractor and pain clinics and were given injections into their spines, knees, and shoulders.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003EFollowing a stroke in his early 60&rsquo;s, Jim Glass sought stem cell treatment in Argentina, China, and Mexico (cost: $200,000). A \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nejm.org\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1056\u002FNEJMc1600188?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&amp;rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&amp;rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\"\u003Espinal cord tumour\u003C\u002Fa\u003E subsequently paralysed his right leg (the stroke had already paralysed his left). DNA analysis indicated the tumour arose from the injected stem cells.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003EA nine-year old boy developed \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.plos.org\u002Fplosmedicine\u002Farticle?id=10.1371\u002Fjournal.pmed.1000029\"\u003Emultiple brain and spinal cord tumours\u003C\u002Fa\u003E following stem cell transplant. Pathological analysis confirmed the spinal tumour contained cells from at least two donors.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhere crowdfunding campaigns fail to reference risk, it could be because some clinics themselves barely convey it. Paul Knoepfler, a biomedical scientist at the University of California, Davis School of Medicine, turned up to one clinic&rsquo;s self-styled educational seminar (used to recruit patients, promising large discounts upon sign-up). Staff, mostly dressed in medical scrubs, neglected to mention any potential adverse events associated with stem cell transplants. The audience did, however, receive a credit application form to complete. Knoepfler \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28170181\"\u003Ewrote\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that the experience was &ldquo;more like attending a persuasive entertainment show or something on a television shopping network than an educational seminar&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1wjp"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs well as underplaying the risks of these therapies, crowdfunding campaigns sometimes overstate its benefits.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Stem cell treatment has helped thousands of children with autism,&rdquo; said one. This campaign, aiming to send a young boy to Panama has raised over $18,000 since September, surpassing its $15,000 goal.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The ALS patients all said it reversed the damage that ALS did to them! Breathing gets better, speaking and swallowing gets better people in wheel chairs were walking in two weeks,&rdquo; claimed another. This campaign raised $1,040 of this patient&rsquo;s $300,000 target to date.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYet many experts argue that these claims are premature.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is currently no proof that stem cell treatment is effective for autism, as Alycia Halladay, chief science officer at the Autism Science Foundation, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogs.scientificamerican.com\u002Fobservations\u002Fhyping-autism-research-news-is-a-disservice-to-people-with-autism\u002F\"\u003Ewrote in Scientific American last year\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Arnold Kriegstein, professor of neurology at the University of California, San Francisco, has similarly \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.the-scientist.com\u002Fnews-opinion\u002Fexperts-question-rationale-for-stem-cell-trial-for-autism-66226\"\u003Eemphasised\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that recent autism trials using stem cell transplant have failed to confirm its efficacy, despite claims to the contrary. He describes \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.spectrumnews.org\u002Fnews\u002Fexperts-balk-at-large-trial-of-stem-cells-for-autism\u002F\"\u003Ethe research as &ldquo;premature&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F29132389\"\u003EUsing stem cell treatments in ALS is especially challenging\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Even if transplanted cells are able to migrate to the areas of damage, mature and integrate into a patient&rsquo;s nervous system before the disease takes its toll (life expectancy is variable but averages two to five years from the time of diagnosis), they will encounter a hostile environment with motor neurons dying around them. At present, most trials are instead focused on using stem cells to create laboratory models of motor neurones on which drugs can be tested and disease mechanisms studied. The MND Association believes that stem cell research is essential in understanding, preventing and curing MND but \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mndassociation.org\u002Fresearch\u002Fabout-mnd-research\u002Fstem-cells\u002Fstem-cell-therapy\u002F\"\u003Estate\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;at present, there is no reliable evidence to suggest that stem cells can be used as an effective treatment&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat Journal of the American Medical Association study found \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjamanetwork.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fjama\u002Farticle-abstract\u002F2680538?redirect=true\"\u003E43.6% of campaigns carried statements that were definitive\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or certain about the effectiveness of treatment. It&rsquo;s not too difficult to trace these overstated claims back to some clinics that use &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.celltherapyjournal.org\u002Farticle\u002FS1465-3249(18)30254-8\u002Fabstract\"\u003Etokens of scientific legitimacy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; &ndash; published articles in journals with little or no peer-review in addition to implied links to preclinical research at reputable but unaffiliated research centres.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1zyq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESometimes the media has helped spread the unfounded hype. In 2014, former soldier James DeLittle, diagnosed with Parkinson&rsquo;s, paid &pound;7,000 ($8,500) for a stem cell procedure in Ukraine. Afterwards, the press frequently quoted the clinic&rsquo;s claim for improvement in 75% of their patients. &ldquo;After just one of the two treatments, the doctor asked me to touch my nose with my eyes closed and I was spot on &mdash; I couldn&rsquo;t believe&nbsp;it,&rdquo; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.express.co.uk\u002Flife-style\u002Fhealth\u002F458028\u002FMy-Parkinson-s-cell-treatment-is-like-a-miracle-says-first-British-patient\"\u003Esaid DeLittle\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at the time. &ldquo;My Parkinson&rsquo;s feels like there is a spring which constantly pulls me to the left hand side. But immediately after the treatment the force didn&rsquo;t feel as strong and my balance was much better as a result.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo years later, a deteriorating DeLittle told the BBC he felt \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Flive\u002Fuk-england-york-north-yorkshire-36791963?ns_mchannel=social&amp;ns_source=twitter&amp;ns_campaign=bbc_live&amp;ns_linkname=57888153e4b050d07851f14f%26Watch%3A%20Unable%20to%20talk%20and%20barely%20able%20to%20walk%2C%20York%20m\"\u003E&ldquo;annoyed, out of pocket and, conned&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Yet most of those 2014 readers will never know that the man who hoped that a stem cell treatment would be &ldquo;a miracle in the making&rdquo; eventually concluded it was nothing more than a scam.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients might not even get what they&rsquo;ve paid for (let alone foregoing effective treatments). Lisa Fortier, regenerative medicine researcher at Cornell University, tested nine products but \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.washingtonpost.com\u002Fnational\u002Fhealth-science\u002Fmiraculous-stem-cell-therapy-has-sickened-people-in-five-states\u002F2019\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fc04b23a4-3539-11e9-854a-7a14d7fec96a_story.html?noredirect=on&amp;noredirect=on&amp;utm_term=.2fb92225fd18\"\u003E&ldquo;none contained stem cells, or a single live cell of any kind&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E So, people are potentially crowdfunding for, and donors contributing to, putative stem cell treatments that have no stem cells.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot all stem cells are created equal, either. Some trials use \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.eurostemcell.org\u002Fmesenchymal-stem-cells-other-bone-marrow-stem-cells\"\u003Emesenchymal stem cells\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; these are cells found in bone marrow, for instance, that are important in making and repairing skeletal tissues, such as cartilage, bone and fat cells. But \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Farticles\u002Fd41586-018-06756-9\"\u003Ethese are now serious questions about whether they even function as stem cells\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Even the person who first named them, Arnold Caplan, believes they should be \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fstemcellsjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1002\u002Fsctm.17-0051\"\u003Erenamed to quell unadulterated hype about their potential\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;I was wrong. I take back the name that I gave these hugely important cells.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1tb9"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ENone of which is to deny the potential for future (authentic) stem cell therapies to help some neurological conditions. The neurodegeneration in Parkinson&rsquo;s is relatively focal &ndash; dopaminergic neurons are progressively lost in a specific region called the midbrain &ndash; which makes it a good potential candidate for cell replacement for some of its symptoms. A Kyoto University trial is using induced pluripotent stem cells, developed by reprogramming skin and other cells \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Farticles\u002Fd41586-018-07407-9\"\u003Eto revert to an embryonic-like state.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E These become ready to morph into other cell types, in this case, dopamine precursor cells. &ldquo;We made a hole in the frontal part of the head's left side and transplanted some 2.4 million cells,&rdquo; researchers excitedly said of their first patient, at the beginning of their two-year trial. Parkinson&rsquo;s UK remain \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.parkinsons.org.uk\u002Fabout-us\u002Fstem-cell-research\"\u003Eoptimistic about the potential of stem cell transplants\u003C\u002Fa\u003E but emphasise research must continue within the UK&rsquo;s &ldquo;rigorous ethical and regulatory framework&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA more prominent surge in interest has centred around multiple sclerosis. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjnnp.bmj.com\u002Fcontent\u002F89\u002F2\u002F147\"\u003EAutologous haematopoietic stem cell transplantation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (AHSCT) aims to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mstrust.org.uk\u002Fa-z\u002Fstem-cell-therapy\"\u003Ereplace or reboot the body&rsquo;s immune system\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: high doses of chemotherapy wipe out a patient&rsquo;s existing immune system which is then rebuilt using their own stem cells collected before chemotherapy.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAHSCT for multiple sclerosis is available in some private clinics in the UK and on the NHS, albeit in a very small number of centres with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mstrust.org.uk\u002Fa-z\u002Fstem-cell-therapy\"\u003Elimited eligibility\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The treatment is aggressive, still largely experimental worldwide, and carries an estimated mortality rate of one in 330.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhy though, is stem cell treatment being offered in this way for multiple sclerosis (MS) in the absence of similar approaches for other neurological conditions?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;In MS the condition has a clear immune basis, so it makes much more logical sense to do bone marrow transplants as a way of treating the disease,&rdquo; explains Roger Barker, a clinical neuroscientist at the University of Cambridge. &nbsp;&ldquo;In neurodegenerative disorders [such as Parkinson&rsquo;s], there is no such evidence, so no logic to doing this.&rdquo; And despite the reasonable promise of using stem cell transplants for multiple sclerosis, many patients \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fresources\u002Fidt-sh\u002Fcaroline_wyatt_multiple_sclerosis\"\u003Ehave been left disappointed with the results\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; as the BBC&rsquo;s Caroline Wyatt reported recently in her quest to treat her own MS.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07l1txt"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESome patient feel they simply don&rsquo;t have time to wait for the culmination of good evidence from protracted clinical trials. Take this fundraising plea from a patient with ALS, a condition in which half of patients die \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cochranelibrary.com\u002Fcdsr\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1002\u002F14651858.CD011742.pub2\u002Fepdf\u002Ffull\"\u003Ewithin three years\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of their first symptoms:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I am down to 32%&nbsp;of breathing, can't talk and loosing (sic) control of my&nbsp;hands and legs. I have where a breathing mask for 12-14 hours a day... PLEASE HELP!&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDoesn&rsquo;t the patient who is &ldquo;down to 32%&nbsp;of breathing&rdquo; have a right to try anything that might save them, crowdfunding to do so, even if that treatment is administered an unregulated clinic? Barker is concerned that it&rsquo;s this vulnerability that is being exploited, citing the potential risks, including tumour formation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut he also believes that legitimate stem cell research will suffer. &ldquo;If it goes wrong, the regulators may ban such therapies for times to come based on the belief that these clinics offer essentially the same therapies as centres which have slowly worked towards clinical trials through proper rational approaches,&rdquo; says Barker.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.fda.gov\u002FNewsEvents\u002FNewsroom\u002FPressAnnouncements\u002Fucm573443.htm\"\u003Eregulators\u003C\u002Fa\u003E must play a role in tandem with \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fstm.sciencemag.org\u002Fcontent\u002F9\u002F397\u002Feaag0426\"\u003Ecross-border partnerships\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, there is a growing consensus that crowdfunding platforms should take responsibility, too. Campaigns for treatments that are unsafe or lacking evidence continue to raise \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjamanetwork.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fjama\u002Farticle-abstract\u002F2708098\"\u003Emillions\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of dollars.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtecting patients\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s true that these platforms can empower patients to explore options, maintain hope, and cover insurance gaps, while enabling families and friends to extend their support. But shouldn&rsquo;t they also ban bad actors and halt the spread of misinformation (campaigns are shared hundreds of thousands of times across social media)?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot necessarily, suggested a GoFundMe \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fgizmodo.com\u002Fgofundme-is-still-enabling-garbage-cancer-treatment-sca-1831472117\"\u003Estatement to Gizmodo\u003C\u002Fa\u003E earlier this year: &ldquo;While we hope to be a helpful resource for personal fundraising, we believe it is not our place to tell them what decision to make.&rdquo; After a call for crowdfunding sites to rigorously vet cancer appeals to protect patients from unproven or dangerous treatments (such as &ldquo;ozone therapy&rdquo; and vitamin infusions), \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fthehill.com\u002Fblogs\u002Fblog-briefing-room\u002F434936-gofundme-bans-donations-for-controversial-cancer-treatments-at\"\u003EGoFundMe has banned users from seeking donations for treatment at certain clinics month\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and now report they are actively evaluating fears around certain stem cell campaigns. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;With these new concerns being raised surrounding certain stem cell clinics, we are taking a thoughtful approach to addressing stem cell campaigns while continuing to provide a safe and secure place for people to fundraise for their needs and causes. We are reaching out to experts and medical regulatory authorities in the space to understand the latest regulatory developments and how these developments affect our customers&rdquo;, they said in a statement.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen presented with similar concerns, JustGiving previously \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bmj.com\u002Fcontent\u002F362\u002Fbmj.k3829\"\u003Estated\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t believe we have the expertise to make a judgment on this.&rdquo; In an email to the BBC, they asserted that they ensure that all the crowdfunding pages obey the legal requirements and assert that &ldquo;the safety and wellbeing of people using our platform, whether they&rsquo;re raising funds or donating to a cause, is always our priority&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETree of Hope, a UK crowdfunding organisation and children&rsquo;s charity, claim a different approach. Their medical committee takes advice on campaigns from the UK Stem Cell Foundation. &ldquo;Families turn to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.treeofhope.org.uk\u002F\"\u003ETree of Hope\u003C\u002Fa\u003E when all other options have been exhausted,&rdquo; says Lee Vallins, deputy chief executive and head of family support at the charity. &ldquo;We work with some amazing, though often desperate parents and ensure we work through options with them, at their pace.&rdquo; But although they have supported a number of families to crowdfund for stem cell transplants, there are safeguards in place.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We readily spend time with parents calling us seeking advice on this type of therapy and we quite often do refuse an application if parents are unwilling to consider recognised clinical trials or alternative options to the treatment,&rdquo; says Vallins. &ldquo;Whilst not one of the larger crowdfunding organisations, we certainly strive to be one of the most ethical through our checks and measures throughout the process.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHunting for hope\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJay Shetty eventually received a two-hour infusion of stem cells through a cannula in his arm at Duke University. What were Shilpa&rsquo;s expectations? &ldquo;I knew it wasn&rsquo;t a cure, I knew he wasn&rsquo;t going to come out of it walking and running. But I thought at least Jay would be able to sit up in six months&rsquo; time, to be honest. Unfortunately, that hasn&rsquo;t happened,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;We haven&rsquo;t seen any dramatic changes but he is not as spastic, he is more aware, for us a family we think it&rsquo;s quite big. It&rsquo;s a sort of foundation for all the physiotherapy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut was the stem cell therapy responsible for this improvement? Perhaps Jay would have acquired more skills as he grew up anyway? &ldquo;It&rsquo;s difficult to pinpoint because we have been doing therapy for a long time,&rdquo; says Shilpa.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo date, stem cell studies on cerebral palsy at \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fstemcellsjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fepdf\u002F10.1002\u002Fsctm.17-0102\"\u003EDuke University Medical Centre\u003C\u002Fa\u003E led by Joanne Kurtzberg, haven&rsquo;t quite lived up to expectations although work is ongoing. In 2017, 63 children with cerebral palsy were randomised to treatment (a single infusion of cord blood) or placebo. Disappointingly, the researchers found no change in the trial&rsquo;s primary endpoint: motor function one year after baseline infusion. They did report better outcomes at higher doses (highlighted in some media coverage) but \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fipscell.com\u002Fpaul\u002F\"\u003EPaul Knoefler\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at the UC Davis School of Medicine isn&rsquo;t persuaded. &ldquo;Based on the small study size, a high-degree of variability within samples in the same groups, changes in the placebo group from what was expected, and the modest nature of the possible differences with the higher dose relative to placebo, I&rsquo;m not convinced the reported effect was meaningful,&rdquo; he says. He also tells me that along with a study from the Duke group on autism, these results &ldquo;don&rsquo;t suggest a strong positive effect of umbilical cord cells for paediatric neurological conditions&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcells4life.com\u002Fjays-journey\u002F\"\u003ECells4Life\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, the cord blood stem cell bank that supported Jay&rsquo;s fundraising, still state on their website that &ldquo;the trials at Duke have shown cord blood can reverse the symptoms of cerebral palsy&rdquo;. (Cells4Life state their mission is to &ldquo;store every baby&rsquo;s cord blood&rdquo;. Their pricing varies between &pound;1,495 ($1,816) and &pound;2,090 ($2,538) with an additional annual storage fee.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Shettys remain undeterred. &ldquo;If we found a match and if Duke open a similar trial I am more than happy to pay for it,&rdquo; says Shilpa. &ldquo;If we have money, we will just keep doing it again and again to be honest. In Jay&rsquo;s case there are a lot of blank spaces in his brain and he needs new cells.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeanwhile, she and other parents will continue to scour the internet late at night, searching for anything might help their children, hunting for hope, calling out for a cure. As long as they do so, stem cell clinics will promise to answer their call.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJules Montague is a writer and neurologist in London. Her first book, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hodder.co.uk\u002Fbooks\u002Fdetail.page?isbn=9781473646940\"\u003ELost and Found\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, explores what remains of the person when the pieces of their mind go missing - from dementia and brain injury to sleep disorders and multiple personality disorder. Her second book,&nbsp;The \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thebookseller.com\u002Fnews\u002Fmontagues-diagnosis-cure-scooped-granta-auction-973186\"\u003EDiagnosis Cure\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, will be published next year and explores how medical diagnosis is deeply tainted by the forces of commerce, imperialism, and sexual discrimination.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin one million Future fans by liking us on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, or follow us on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Capital, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms-12"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fhealth","future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-08-21T00:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The 'unwarranted hype' of stem cell therapies","headlineShort":"The unproven hype of stem cell therapy?","image":["p07l1ysn"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e982150f363927515d677c8"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":["p07l1yw9"],"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fmedicine"],"summaryLong":"Campaigns for expensive stem cell therapies can now be found on many crowdfunding websites. But are the patients and the donors being misled about the benefits and the risks?","summaryShort":"Patients are being misled about the benefits and risks of the costly treatments","tag":["tag\u002Fcomment-analysis"],"creationDateTime":"2019-08-20T23:50:16.002296Z","entity":"article","guid":"321ddbc0-64bb-4d90-baa4-843ec4b04c98","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:11:31.366112Z","project":"future","slug":"20190819-the-unwarranted-hype-of-stem-cell-therapies-for-autism-ms","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006373},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief","_id":"5e9820a3f363927515d0d2d1","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fmithu-storoni"],"bodyIntro":"Are we really more stressed than ever before? In an essay based on her recent book Stress-Proof, Mithu Storoni explains how modern life may have amplified our anxiety, and the best ways to reduce its impact on our bodies and minds","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn November 2017, two eye surgeons from a hospital in Beirut reported an intriguing case of visual loss in a colleague. A specialist in the retina, the colleague had suddenly developed a patch of blurry vision in one eye just a day or two after an intensely stressful day in the operating room. This was not the first time it had happened. The surgeon had experienced four such episodes in just a year, each preceded by a stressful day of operating.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe retinal surgeon was diagnosed with central serous chorioretinopathy (CSCR). A small amount of fluid had collected beneath a tiny region of the surgeon's retina, causing it to temporarily detach. The condition resolved after a few weeks, and a strict stress-management plan prevented another episode from happening again.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst described in 1866, CSCR has been tentatively linked to stress ever since World War Two, when \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.lww.com\u002Fpsychosomaticmedicine\u002FCitation\u002F1947\u002F03000\u002FCentral_Angiospastic_Retinopathy__A_Psychosomatic.5.aspx\"\u003Eseveral cases were reported in military personnel\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Although subsequent research has associated CSCR with stress-related mechanistic pathways, it is often labelled &ldquo;idiopathic&rdquo; (arising from an unknown cause) if no trigger other than stress is found. Departing from convention, the surgeons labelled the condition \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC5669318\u002F\"\u003E&ldquo;Operating Room CSCR&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E identifying stress as its cause.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReflecting on what had made their colleague vulnerable to stress, the surgeons noted new surgical techniques made possible with better technology had stretched the physical limits of what a surgeon is able to do. While this progress had expanded the scope of surgery, operating at these limits placed immense mental strain on the surgeon.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180219-toxic-perfectionism-is-on-the-rise\"\u003EThe dangerous downsides of perfectionism\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180201-what-i-learned-by-testing-my-stress-levels-on-social-media\"\u003EWhat I learned testing my stress levels on social media\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160721-the-reasons-why-exhaustion-and-burnout-are-so-common\"\u003EWhy exhaustion and burnout are so common\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 1959, management pundit Peter Drucker had predicted a dramatic transition in the nature of work would take place 50 years later. He coined a term for this new kind of work, &ldquo;knowledge work&rdquo; and anticipated the change would involve a move from physical to mental effort. He later wrote the centre of gravity of work would shift to &ldquo;the man who puts to work what he has between his ears rather than the skill of his hands&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe evolution of eye surgery has validated some of Drucker&rsquo;s predictions. As technology improves, it transmutes the physical skill of the surgeon&rsquo;s hands into the mental skills of analysis and concentration.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The evolving nature of work demands less from the body and more from the mind &ndash; meaning the mind is becoming a greater victim of occupational hazards","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eye surgery operating room is to some degree a microcosm of today&rsquo;s global workplace, where the evolving nature of work demands less from the body and more from the mind. Consequently, the mind is becoming a greater victim of occupational hazards.&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.hse.gov.uk\u002Fstatistics\u002Fcausdis\u002Fstress.pdf\"\u003EHealth and Safety Executive (HSE) of the United Kingdom\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, stress, depression or anxiety accounted for 57% of all &ldquo;sick days&rdquo; in 2017\u002F2018. The mind&rsquo;s rising leverage over productivity is prompting interest in what might be impeding its performance. The focus has fallen on stress.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07kj99d"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJ&aacute;nos Hugo Bruno \"Hans\" Selye, a Canadian-Hungarian physician, coined the first definition of &ldquo;stress&rdquo; in the 1930s. He borrowed the word from 17th Century English physicist Robert Hooke, whose Law of 1658 describes the relationship between physical stress on a material and its consequence, strain. Selye reportedly regretted using the word &ldquo;stress&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;strain&rdquo;, which left stress with a legacy of some ambiguity. It occupies a rare niche in the English language in meaning both the cause and the consequence &ndash; of itself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The stress from being restrained for a few hours increased the number of &ldquo;newborn&rdquo; brain cells in a part of the rat&rsquo;s brain","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch since Selye&rsquo;s time has revealed an acute stress reaction is built upon a rich tapestry of processes. We know today that bungee jumpers&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F22283617\"\u003Ebecome insulin resistant\u003C\u002Fa\u003E immediately following a bungee jump,&nbsp;and the stress of&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F27486621\u002F\"\u003Electuring 200 students raises markers of inflammation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in college professors. These processes offer a survival advantage under threat. The temporary insulin resistance, for instance, ensures sugar reaches a brain under duress, while inflammation holds a protective shield against unwelcome visitors entering through battle wounds.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe effects of a healthy, acute stress reaction are mostly temporary, ceasing when a stressful experience is over, and any lasting effects can sometimes leave us better than we were before. Studies on rats, for instance, found that the stress from being restrained for a few hours may \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3628086\u002F\"\u003Eincrease the number of &ldquo;newborn&rdquo; brain cells\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in a part of the rat&rsquo;s brain, which can correspond to better performance in certain kinds of memory tests.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStress that is too frequent, too intense or constantly present, however, puts us under prolonged strain. Many of the players in the stress response have so-called&nbsp;&ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3186928\u002F\"\u003Enon-linear dose-dependent actions\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; meaning their effects change course with prolonged activity. As a result, chronic stress induces a gradual, persistent shift in psychological and physiological parameters that tips the scales towards disorder along different pathways.&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sympathetic and parasympathetic arms of the autonomic nervous system &ndash; a nerve network controlling involuntary processes such as blood pressure, breathing and digestion &ndash; play a pivotal role in orchestrating the acute stress response. During times of fear or anger, sympathetic activity (responsible for the &ldquo;fight-or-flight&rdquo; response) temporarily rises and parasympathetic activity (underlining &ldquo;rest-and-digest&rdquo; responses) falls. If this pattern of activity persists in the absence of stress, however, it can tilt us towards hypertension and other illnesses. Similarly, while temporary emotional reactivity in acute stress helps us predict danger, a sustained change in the dynamics of emotion regulation can tilt us towards mood disorders.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStructural change\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic stress is suspected of playing a role in the rising global burden of hypertension and&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F30641693\"\u003Etype 2 diabetes\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and pushes&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F27520750\"\u003Erats into major depression\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;Corroborating&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F29580891\"\u003Eobservations\u003C\u002Fa\u003E from&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F25529195\"\u003Eanimal studies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and early human studies suggest chronic stress may even change the structure of the brain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28108490\"\u003EIn the first study of its kind, Ivanka Savic and colleagues at Sweden&rsquo;s Karolinska Institute\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and Stockholm University recently compared the brains of people suffering from work-related chronic stress to those of healthy, less stressed counterparts using structural magnetic resonance imaging techniques. They found a difference in regions active in attention allocation, decision-making, memory and emotion processing. In the stressed subjects, the prefrontal cortex appeared thinner, the amygdala appeared thicker and the caudate nucleus was smaller. The thinning in the prefrontal cortex correlated with worse emotion regulation.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"A three month-long stress-rehabilitation program reversed thinning in the prefrontal cortex","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETo establish whether chronic stress was simply correlated to the changes or had caused the changes in the stressed individuals, the researchers scanned their brains again after a three month-long stress-rehabilitation program based on cognitive therapy and breathing exercises. The thinning in the prefrontal cortex was reversed. While the study had limitations (there was no &ldquo;untreated stressed&rdquo; control group), this reversal hinted at the possibility that chronic stress might have caused the thinning. Other studies have found that high circulating levels of the hormone&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fn.neurology.org\u002Fcontent\u002F91\u002F21\u002Fe1961\"\u003Ecortisol correlates with worse memory\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and thinning in parts of the brain, even at a relatively young age.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes may partly be the consequence of the plastic nature of our brains, a manifestation of the brain&rsquo;s extraordinary talent of adapting to whatever is demanded of it. In the middle of combat, for example, heightened emotional reactivity is a survival advantage, while higher cognitive functions become redundant. Recalibrating the brain&rsquo;s baseline state to increase efficiency in this way can save a combat soldier&rsquo;s life. In the setting of a workplace that relies on focus and complex decision-making, however, compromised emotion regulation and a decline in working memory will limit productivity. The change in the brain&rsquo;s structure is maladaptive.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07kj9g4"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic stress often strikes through a psychosocial route and is influenced by perception. While this makes the empirical study of chronic stress challenging, it also uncovers a potential path for managing chronic stress: one&rsquo;s perceptual experience.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne example is the effect of rumination. Replaying the memory of a stressful experience after it is over can activate similar pathways in the brain as the actual experience. This can keep the stress reaction &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hindawi.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fijhy\u002F2012\u002F453465\u002F\"\u003Eswitched on\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; even if a stressor is no longer there and&nbsp;cause&nbsp;the experience to be&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F17559717\"\u003Eperceived as more distressing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E than it actually was. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F20846182\"\u003EPreventing people from ruminating lowers their blood pressure faster\u003C\u002Fa\u003E after acute stress. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hindawi.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fijhy\u002F2012\u002F453465\u002F\"\u003EChronic stress has been linked\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to hypertension and&nbsp;in a small, randomised trial,\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC6128963\u002F\"\u003E&nbsp;US researchers, including Lynn Clemow at Columbia University Medical Center, used stress management training\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (based on a cognitive-behavioral group workshop) to effectively lower systolic blood pressure in patients with hypertension. The decline in pressure correlated with a decline in depressive rumination.&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28866110\"\u003Eperceptual element of stress\u003C\u002Fa\u003E may be the reason some mind-body interventions such as yoga,&nbsp;breathing techniques and focused-attention meditation can benefit stress management through effects on&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F23935694\"\u003Eimproving emotional regulation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, reducing stress reactivity and&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F29154056\"\u003Espeeding up recovery\u003C\u002Fa\u003E after stress.&nbsp;It may also explain why some techniques such as mindfulness meditation&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F24767614?access_num=24767614&amp;link_type=MED&amp;dopt=Abstract\"\u003Ehave shown mixed results\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in controlled studies. It is possible the technique of mindfulness meditation can&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.plos.org\u002Fplosone\u002Farticle?id=10.1371\u002Fjournal.pone.0216643\"\u003Einvite rumination and repetitive negative thoughts in some individuals\u003C\u002Fa\u003E but not in others.&nbsp;Perceived stress can vary with genetic and epigenetic factors, individual traits, patterns of thought and behaviour, and the journey of one&rsquo;s life so far.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatus and control\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn some ways, the brain mimics a prediction machine that actively infers its environment to create a perceived representation of reality.&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F?term=28576664\"\u003EA perception of uncertainty\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, unpredictability or a lack of control can signal there is a flaw in its model of reality and promote stress.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA practical demonstration of this theory lies in the way&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC5224385\u002F\"\u003Estress is moderated by social status\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Having a high social status tempers your reaction to psychological stress, but if you think your social status might be challenged, having a lower social status may be better. This effect has been attributed to&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28977477\"\u003Enot feeling in control\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and may play a role in why&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F17907819\"\u003Ecompetition, inequality and feeling judged\u003C\u002Fa\u003E can generate stress.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07kj9z8"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a predictable world over which you have perfect control, a cause should lead to a predictable effect.&nbsp;A frequent mismatch between the effort you put in and the reward you receive for your effort frustrates this sense of perceived control.&nbsp;Consequently, an&nbsp;&ldquo;effort-reward imbalance&rdquo; is a source of chronic \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F9547031\"\u003Estress in the workplace\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It is associated with a raised blood pressure in&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F31044447\"\u003Efemale Las Vegas hotel room\u003C\u002Fa\u003E cleaners, with burnout in&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F30906189\"\u003Epolice officers in Buffalo, New York\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and with metabolic syndrome in fit,&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4671563\u002F\"\u003Estate police workers in Genoa, Italy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The effort of having to deal with a mismatch between effort and reward at work every day is&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fpublication\u002F241843437_Interaction_Effects_of_Effort-Reward_Imbalance_and_Overcommitment_on_Emotional_Exhaustion_and_Job_Performance\"\u003Eemotionally exhausting\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and takes a toll on mental performance. In a study on Australian horse jockeys, experiencing high levels of effort-reward imbalance during times of intense stress correlated with an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28732265\"\u003Eimpairment in decision-making\u003C\u002Fa\u003E comparable to that associated with a blood alcohol concentration of 0.08%.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s not just the nature of our social interactions that could exacerbate stress. The impact of some facets of urbanised life on stress reactivity may have also been underestimated.&nbsp;An apparently &ldquo;soft&rdquo; factor like exposure to nature&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F?term=viewing+nature+scenes+postively+affects\"\u003Ecan hasten recovery following stress\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and lower&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F31019479\"\u003Emarkers of stress\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;Bright light or blue night exposure late in the evening from the use of LED screens can delay the release of melatonin, a hormone that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cochrane.org\u002FCD009861\u002FANAESTH_melatonin-pre-and-postoperative-anxiety-adults\"\u003Ehas been shown to reduce anxiety\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F18787373\"\u003ELow-intensity exercise\u003C\u002Fa\u003E reduces circulating levels of cortisol, yet the need for frequent movement is often redundant.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrbanisation is increasing the consumption of processed food and an ultra-processed diet&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F30982472\"\u003Ehas been linked\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to the&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F31055621\"\u003Eincidence of depressive symptoms\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in at least two large cohorts.&nbsp;Our dietary habits modify the micro-organisms living in the digestive tract and these micro-organisms, through cross-talk with immune cells and other routes, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190218-how-the-bacteria-inside-you-could-affect-your-mental-health\"\u003Ecan influence how the mind reacts to stress\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is some evidence that modulating gut microbiota with specific foods or taking probiotics can help&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fgpsych.bmj.com\u002Fcontent\u002F32\u002F2\u002Fe100056\"\u003Ereduce symptoms of anxiety\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Early results suggest taking either a single strain or a combination of probiotics may&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.lww.com\u002Fajg\u002FAbstract\u002Fpublishahead\u002FBifidobacterium_longum_1714__Strain_Modulates.99692.aspx\"\u003Ereduce mental fatigue\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC6430409\u002F\"\u003Eimprove cognitive performance\u003C\u002Fa\u003E during stress &ndash; but not in the absence of stress.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07kj8tl"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a 2015 exhibition at the Petit Palais in Paris, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwsimag.com\u002Fart\u002F14463-thomas-lerooy-beauty-in-the-shadow-of-the-stars\"\u003EBelgian artist Thomas Lerooy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E presented a perceptive visual metaphor of mental stress in an exhibit aptly named &ldquo;Not enough brain to survive&rdquo;. The bronze sculpture depicted a classically beautiful body weighed down by a grotesquely enlarged, rather sad-looking head.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike Lerooy&rsquo;s piece, the human head does not expand and sink to the ground as its stress load grows heavier. Mental fatigue after a complex ophthalmic procedure is invisible. The surgeon does not gasp for air nor perspire. The picture painted by mental exhaustion is strikingly abstract compared to the well-recognised signs of physical exertion.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMental strain is a performance-limiting factor in an age where physical load is increasingly converted into mental load. As we transition further into the information age, it is time for the enigma of chronic stress to finally move into the spotlight.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mithustoroni.com\u002F\"\u003EMithu Storoni \u003C\u002Fa\u003Etrained as an eye surgeon and studied diseases affecting the visual brain before writing Stress-Proof: The Ultimate Guide to Living a Stress-Free Life (Hodder\u002FYellow Kite).\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003