future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":["p07kjb59"],"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fmedicine"],"summaryLong":"Are we really more stressed than ever before? Mithu Storoni explains how modern life may have amplified our anxiety, and the best ways to reduce its impact on our bodies and minds","summaryShort":"In the Information Age, we need new ways to cope with our workload","tag":["tag\u002Fmedicine"],"creationDateTime":"2019-08-14T00:50:26.933965Z","entity":"article","guid":"2fe7342a-9ee2-45ac-9fd4-f535bd9a1540","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:11:31.366112Z","project":"future","slug":"20190813-burnout-anxiety-stress-proof-relief","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006373},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming","_id":"5e9820a1f363927515d0cba1","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Ftim-smedley"],"bodyIntro":"Timber structures would allow us to draw carbon from the air and store it in our homes and offices – leading some to believe that wooden buildings are the future of architecture.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EI&rsquo;m standing in a seemingly ordinary construction site of an unremarkable office block in east London. The seven-storey building is about two-thirds complete &ndash; the basic structure and staircases are in place, with plastering and wiring just beginning. But as I walk around, something different slowly reveals itself. The construction site is quiet and clean &ndash; it even smells good. And there&rsquo;s an awful lot of wood. Building sites typically feature wood as the mould to pour the concrete into. But here, the wood \u003Cem\u003Eis\u003C\u002Fem\u003E the concrete.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Because a timber building weighs 20% of a concrete building, the gravitational load is vastly reduced,&rdquo; enthuses Andrew Waugh, the architect, who shows me around. &ldquo;That means we need minimal foundations, we don&rsquo;t need massive amounts of concrete in the ground. We have a timber core, timber walls and timber floor slabs &ndash; so we reduce the amount of steel down to a bare minimum.&rdquo; Steel is typically used to form the main internal supports or to reinforce concrete in most large modern buildings. In this wooden building, however, there are relatively few steel sections. Those that remain are bolted together like a Meccano set, to be easily taken apart at the end of (or during) the building&rsquo;s life. &ldquo;If you wanted to put a staircase right here,&rdquo; says Waugh, pointing to the ceiling, &ldquo;you unscrew that [steel] beam there, get a chainsaw and cut a hole in the timber [floor].&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Globally, enough concrete is poured each year to cover the whole of England","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOur dependency on concrete and steel to build everything from homes to sports stadiums, comes at a severe environmental cost. Concrete is responsible for \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.chathamhouse.org\u002Fsites\u002Fdefault\u002Ffiles\u002Fpublications\u002F2018-06-13-making-concrete-change-cement-lehne-preston-final.pdf\"\u003E4-8%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;of the world&rsquo;s carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions. Second only to water, it is the most widely used substance on Earth, accounting for around 85% of all mining and linked to an \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fthe-world-is-facing-a-global-sand-crisis-83557\"\u003Ealarming depletion of the world&rsquo;s sand\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Globally, enough concrete is poured each year to cover the whole of England.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also enjoy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180918-the-outrageous-plan-to-haul-icebergs-to-africa\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe outrageous plans to haul icebergs to Africa\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190612-the-poisons-released-by-melting-arctic-ice\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe poisons released by melting ice\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190220-how-artificially-brightened-clouds-could-stop-climate-change\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EHow brightened clouds could fight climate change \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome architects such as Waugh are therefore arguing for &ndash; and pressing ahead with &ndash; a return to wood as our primary building material. Wood from managed forestry actually stores carbon as opposed to emitting it: as trees grow, they absorb CO2 from the atmosphere. As a rule of thumb, a cubic metre of wood contains around a tonne of CO2 (more or less, depending on the species of tree) &ndash; which is \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.swst.org\u002Fwp\u002Fmeetings\u002FAM10\u002Fppts\u002FLabbe.pdf\"\u003Esimilar to 350 litres of gasoline\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07h3bx7"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ENot only does wood remove more CO2 from the atmosphere than it adds through manufacture, but by replacing carbon-intensive materials such as concrete or steel it doubles its contribution to lowering CO2. A recent advisory report to the UK government on the uses of &ldquo;Biomass in a low-carbon economy&rdquo; found that, &ldquo;the greatest levels of [greenhouse gas] abatement from biomass currently occur when wood is used as a construction material&hellip; to both store carbon and displace high carbon cement, brick and steel.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBetween 15% and 28% of new homes built in the UK annually use timber frame construction, capturing over one million tonnes of CO2 a year as a result. Increasing the use of timber in construction could triple that amount, the report concluded. &ldquo;Savings of a similar magnitude may also be possible in the commercial and industrial sectors by utilising new engineered wood systems such as cross-laminated timber.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECross-laminated timber, or CLT, is the primary material on the construction site Andrew Waugh shows me around in east London. Because it&rsquo;s described as an &ldquo;engineered wood&rdquo;, I expect to see something similar to chipboard or plywood. But CLT just looks like ordinary 3m (10ft) planks of wood, one inch thick, replete with knot-holes and splinters. The ingenuity is that the planks are made stronger by gluing them in layers of three, with each layer perpendicular to the other. This means that the CLT &ldquo;doesn&rsquo;t bow or bend, it has integral strength in two directions&rdquo;, says Waugh. &ldquo;[A CLT] wall supports the floor above, with a horizontal strength to carry a load above it, acting like a long beam&rdquo;. That, he says, &ldquo;changes architecture&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaving built with CLT for a decade now, Waugh believes it can achieve anything a concrete and steel building can, and more besides. It was invented in the 1990s, partly in response to &ldquo;the death of the furniture and paper industries&rdquo;, says Waugh. &ldquo;Sixty percent of Austria is forest and they needed to find a new sales outlet. So, they came up with cross-laminated timber.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07h3c63"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOther engineered woods such as plywood and MDF are around 10% adhesive (glue), often urea-formaldehyde,&nbsp;which can produce hazardous chemicals during recycling or incineration. CLT, however, is below 1% adhesive, and typically uses a bio-based polyurethane. The planks are bonded together under heat and pressure to fuse that small amount of adhesive using the moisture of the wood. To look at, smell and touch, it&rsquo;s as pure wood as a child&rsquo;s tree house &ndash; knots and all.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany CLT factories in Austria are even powered by renewable biomass using the offcuts, branches and twigs. Some factories produce enough electricity to power the surrounding communities.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite the fact that CLT was invented in Austria, Waugh&rsquo;s London-based architecture practice, Waugh Thistleton, was the first to use it to construct a multi-storey building. Murray Grove, an otherwise ordinary nine-floor apartment block with grey cladding, caused &ldquo;shock and horror in Austria&rdquo; when it was being built in 2009, says Waugh. CLT had only ever been used for &ldquo;nice and simple two-storey houses&rdquo;, whereas anything taller reverted to concrete and steel. But for Murray Grove, the entire structure above the first floor slab is comprised of CLT panels, with all walls, floor slabs and lift cores formed from timber, like a honeycomb block.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe project has since inspired hundreds of architects to build tall with CLT, from the 55m Brock Commons Tallwood House, in Vancouver, Canada, to the 84m, 24-storey 'HoHo Tower' currently under construction in Vienna, Austria.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Since 2001, Canada&rsquo;s forests have emitted more CO2 than they absorbed","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ERecently there have been calls for \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fenvironment\u002F2019\u002Fjul\u002F04\u002Fplanting-billions-trees-best-tackle-climate-crisis-scientists-canopy-emissions\"\u003Etree planting on a colossal scale\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to capture CO2 and curb climate change. However, whilst young trees are efficient and effective carbon sinks, the same is not so true for mature trees. The Earth maintains a balanced carbon cycle &ndash; trees (along with all other plants and animals) grow using carbon, they fall and die, and release that carbon again. That balance was knocked out of kilter when humans discovered ancient stores of carbon in the form of coal and oil, which had been captured during previous carbon cycles, and began burning them, releasing the resulting CO2 into our atmosphere far faster than the current cycle can deal with.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07h393d"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMany pine trees in managed forests, such as the European spruce, take roughly 80 years to reach maturity, being net absorbers of carbon during those years of growth &ndash; but once they reach maturity, they shed roughly as much carbon through the decomposition of needles and fallen branches as they absorb. As was the case in Austria in the 1990s, plummeting demand for paper and wood saw huge swathes of managed forests globally fall into disuse. Rather than return to pristine wilderness, these monocrops cover forest floors in acidic pine needles and dead branches. Canada's great forests for example \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cbc.ca\u002Fnews\u002Fcanada\u002Fcalgary\u002Fcanada-forests-carbon-sink-or-source-1.5011490\"\u003Ehave actually emitted more carbon than they absorb since 2001\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, thanks to mature trees no longer being actively felled.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArguably, the best form of carbon sequestration is to \u003Cem\u003Echop down\u003C\u002Fem\u003E trees: to restore our sustainable, managed forests, and use the resulting wood as a building material. Managed forests certified by the Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) typically plant two to three trees for every tree felled &ndash; meaning the more demand there is for wood, the greater the growth in both forest cover and CO2-hungry young trees.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERewilding and protecting virgin forests is essential. But unmanaged monocrops help no-one, and floors full of dry pine needles are also the primary cause of wildfires &ndash; something that North America and many parts of the world experience on a now annual basis. Managed harvesting greatly reduces that risk.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese benefits have not been lost on the US authorities. Melissa Jenkins, of the US Federal Forest Service, explained at a recent meeting of the Environmental&nbsp;and&nbsp;Energy Study Institute&nbsp;(EESI), that &ldquo;we have a situation of overstocked forests: if a wildfire blows through, these fires burn hotter, they burn faster and they take a lot more effort to put out&hellip; If we can build markets for these wood products, landowners will be more likely to sustainably manage or sustainably thin their land.&rdquo; She highlights that CLT in particular as having the potential to reduce &ldquo;wildfire risk [and] support rural economic development and jobs&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07h39fh"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe market seems to agree. Less than five years after its arrival on US shores, there are now CLT projects underway in almost every mainland US state. More importantly, unlike the UK &ndash; which currently imports all of its CLT &ndash; the US is investing in domestic CLT manufacturing, with factories in Montana and Oregon, and more planned in Maine, Utah, Illinois, Texas, Washington State, Alabama and Arkansas. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bizjournals.com\u002Ftwincities\u002Fnews\u002F2018\u002F05\u002F02\u002Famazon-says-minneapolis-tech-office-part-of-a.html\"\u003EAmazon&rsquo;s new &ldquo;tech-hub&rdquo; building in Minneapolis\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is made from nail laminated timber (like CLT, but \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thinkwood.com\u002Fproducts-and-systems\u002Fnail-laminated-timber\"\u003Eusing nails rather than glue\u003C\u002Fa\u003E). The 2018 Timber Innovation Act also included provisions for research and development into mass timber.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStructures using wooden materials also tend to be quicker and easier to build, therefore reducing labour costs, transport fuel and on-site energy use. Alison Wring, director of Aecom, an infrastructure company, cites a CLT residential block of around 200 apartments that &ldquo;took just 16 weeks [to build]&hellip; whereas if it had been done traditionally with a concrete frame it would have taken at least 26 weeks.&rdquo; Similarly, says Waugh, a recent 16,000-square-metre CLT building he worked on, &ldquo;would have needed around 1,000 cement truck deliveries for the frame alone. To deliver all the CLT, we needed just 92 deliveries.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther countries are turning to timber, too. Monika Lebeničnik, a sales engineer&nbsp;for Ledinek Engineering, an Austrian-Slovenian firm that makes the presses for CLT factories, sent me her order sheet going back to 2013. It begins with a trickle of orders from Austria and Scandinavia. But from 2017 onwards, there is sudden take-up from Japan, France, Australia, Latvia and Canada. &ldquo;Annual capacity of such lines range from 25,000 to 50,000 cubic meters [of CLT],&rdquo; explains Lebeničnik. Data suggests that 1,000 cubic metres of CLT equates to around 500 harvested trees; factories processing 50,000 cubic metres are therefore trapping the sequestered carbon of 25,000 trees per year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are even advantages that make the material particularly attractive to countries like Japan, since it has been found to perform well in earthquake tests. A joint Italian-Japanese research team built a seven-storey CLT building and tested it on a &ldquo;shake table&rdquo; (a cool but eerie \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?v=T08KRyVhyeo\"\u003Evideo of this exists on Youtube\u003C\u002Fa\u003E). They found that it could withstand shaking at the level of the 1995 earthquake in Kobe, Japan, which destroyed more than 50,000 buildings. With serendipitous timing, says Waugh, &ldquo;the Americans planted lots of trees in Japan as part of the Marshall Plan &ndash; that was over 60 years ago, and they are reaching maturity now&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECounterintuitively, CLT also performs well in fires. It is designed to withstand heats of up to 270C before it begins to char &ndash; the charring on the outside then acts as a protective layer for the structural density of the wood behind it. By contrast, at similar temperatures \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hindawi.com\u002Fjournals\u002Fisrn\u002F2014\u002F468510\u002F\"\u003Econcrete can spall and crack\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.steelconstruction.info\u002FFire_damage_assessment_of_hot_rolled_structural_steelwork#Reasons_for_fire_damage\"\u003Esteel loses its strength\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot everyone believes that the future is CLT, however. When I ask Chris&nbsp;Cheeseman, professor of materials resources engineering at Imperial College London, whether wood could usurp concrete as our primary building material, his response is blunt. &ldquo;No. That isn&rsquo;t going to happen. It might happen locally with some small schemes. But you&rsquo;ve got to appreciate the massive use of concrete, and the massive importance of concrete to infrastructure and society. It is an exceptionally good material because of its functionality and its robustness.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07h3byz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is also the &ldquo;end of life&rdquo; question. Carbon only remains trapped in the wood for as long as the building remains standing or is reused in another building &ndash; if it rots or is burned for energy, then all the stored carbon is released. Doug King, a chartered engineer and building sustainability advisor, tells me, &ldquo;unless we attend to the disposal of timber materials at their end of life there is no guarantee that the overall cycle is making a positive benefit to society.&rdquo; Previous research work by Arup in 2014 estimated that half of all construction timber ends up in landfill, 36% is recycled and the remaining 14% burnt for biomass energy.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite these issues, Waugh remains ambitious. The average lifetime of a building is 50-60 years &ndash; that, he believes, is more than enough time for architects and engineers to work out the re-use and recycling issues. Turning it into \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.elegantembellishments.net\u002Fmade-from-air\"\u003Ebiochar could be one possibility\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Waugh&rsquo;s buildings are made to be easy to take apart for re-use by future generations.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFundamentally he &ndash; along with a growing \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thinkwood.com\u002Fnews\u002F100-projects-uk-clt-explores-pioneering-mass-timber-projects\"\u003Egroup of international architects\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; is convinced that mass adoption of CLT is an important weapon in the fight against climate change. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not a fad or a fashion,&rdquo; he tells me as we finish the tour of his east London build, and I take my final, incongruous breath of the forest air. &ldquo;The largest commercial developer in the UK have just bought this building. For me, that&rsquo;s where you want to be&hellip; I want this to be mainstream. Everybody should be building with this.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI return to my original question: could we realistically return to wood as our primary building material? &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not only realistic, it&rsquo;s imperative,&rdquo; argues Waugh. &ldquo;It has to happen. In architecture you always go back to the sketch: the sketch is climate change.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETim Smedley is a sustainability writer, based in the UK. His first book is \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bloomsbury.com\u002Fuk\u002Fclearing-the-air-9781472953315\u002F\"\u003EClearing the Air: The Beginning and the End of Air Pollution\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Join more than one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Capital, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming-14"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-07-25T01:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Could wooden buildings be a solution to climate change?","headlineShort":"Why we should live in wooden buildings","image":["p07h3c9d"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e982150f363927515d677c8"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fclimatechange"],"summaryLong":"Timber structures would allow us to draw carbon from the air and store it in our homes and offices – leading some to believe that wooden buildings are the future of architecture.","summaryShort":"Replacing concrete with timber could avert climate change","tag":["tag\u002Fclimatechange"],"creationDateTime":"2019-07-25T00:00:36.530259Z","entity":"article","guid":"a9972abc-13cb-4eee-9b89-13fabc22fde9","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming","modifiedDateTime":"2020-03-06T09:37:15.966193Z","project":"future","slug":"20190717-climate-change-wooden-architecture-concrete-global-warming","cacheLastUpdated":1587443006374},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution","_id":"5e9820a7f363927515d0e3ba","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fbrandon-ambrosino"],"bodyIntro":"From reproduction without sex to open relationships, our attitudes towards sex may evolve rapidly in the near future, predicts the writer Brandon Ambrosino.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhy do we have sex?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany of our answers probably include a reference to reproduction. Sex is the primary way that babies are made.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut what will we think about sex if it has almost nothing to do with procreation?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince the birth of the world&rsquo;s first &ldquo;test tube baby&rdquo; in 1978, around \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fedition.cnn.com\u002F2018\u002F07\u002F03\u002Fhealth\u002Fworldwide-ivf-babies-born-study\u002Findex.html\"\u003Eeight million people have been born by IVF\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. And the number may vastly increase in the future as our tools to identify genetic risks in embryos become more sophisticated. &ldquo;My strongest prediction is in the future people will still have sex &ndash;&nbsp;but not as often for the purpose of making babies,&rdquo; Henry T Greely, author of The End of Sex And The Future of Human Reproduction, tells me over the phone. &ldquo;In 20 to 40 years, most people all over the world with good health coverage will choose to conceive in a lab.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGreely&rsquo;s book explores some of the legal and ethical challenges facing the science of preimplantation genetic diagnosis (PGD). &ldquo;Like most things, there will be a fair amount of visceral negative reaction initially, but as time goes on and kids [born via PGD] prove not to have two heads and a tail,&rdquo; the public will come not only to tolerate but to prefer reproducing non-sexually.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd in that world &ndash; a world where babies are made in labs; where pregnancy-via-sexual intercourse is elected only by a minority of women; where sexual ethics have nothing to do with procreative possibilities &ndash; what will sex mean?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frhtm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;What is sex \u003Cem\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fem\u003E?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat&rsquo;s a question David Halperin asks in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.journals.uchicago.edu\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1086\u002F688306?mobileUi=0\"\u003Ea provocative essay of the same name\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Sex, we reason, must always have a \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E. Such reasoning isn&rsquo;t necessarily a bad thing. After all, to be human means to be curious, intellectually and emotionally. Experiencing sex and theorising about what it could mean seems very natural for animals that spend much of our time engaging in higher-level criticism.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiologically, there is one an obvious why to human sex. We have sex because it fulfills biological drives, including the necessary drives to procreate and bond. In fact, these are the two \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003Es that have passed down to us in the Western tradition, both of which are organised around a telos, or end goal.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs I wrote in a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20170315-the-invention-of-heterosexuality\"\u003Eprevious article\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, it was the stoics who, attempting to curb self-indulgence, tried to fit sex into a scheme of meaning: indulging in the pleasure of sex was alright as long as it was \u003Cem\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fem\u003E the purposes of making babies. This ethic worked its way into the Christian tradition, famously through Augustine, and continues to wield enormous influence in the West. According to this framework, sex is ethical when it is practised primarily for procreation. (To clarify, though this is presented as a Christian ethic, its origins lie elsewhere. In fact, the biblical book Song of Solomon celebrates wild, passionate, erotic sex on its own terms, between two lovers &ndash; not between a husband and wife, as later Christian commentators wrongly interpreted the poem.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other important \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E for sex comes from Aristotle, as Halperin points out. In Prior Analytics from the 4th Century BCE, the Greek philosopher offers the following syllogism:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;To be loved, then, is preferable to intercourse, according to the nature of erotic desire. Erotic desire, then, is more a desire for love than for intercourse. If it is most of all for that, that is also its end. Either intercourse, then, is not an end at all or it is for the sake of being loved.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor Aristotle, as Halperin explains, &ldquo;Love is the telos of erotic desire. It is not love that aims at sex as its goal&hellip; It is sex that aims at love.&rdquo; The real reason we have sex, according to Aristotle&rsquo;s proof, is not because we want to have sex, but because we want to love and be loved. Sex is not about something, but about something else, something \u003Cem\u003Ehigher\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, something \u003Cem\u003Enobler\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELike many people, Aristotle takes it for granted that sex and love go hand in hand &ndash; but he never seeks to demonstrate the soundness of this assumption. What he \u003Cem\u003Edoes\u003C\u002Fem\u003E demonstrate, however, at least as Halperin reads him, is that &ldquo;sex is not the final aim of erotic desire&rdquo;. And if that&rsquo;s the case, then Halperin thinks the most interesting question to ask isn&rsquo;t about the relationship between sex and love but the surprising relationship between sex and erotic desire. If Aristotle is correct, then sex has no erotic purpose &ndash; its real aim lies elsewhere. In short, sex isn&rsquo;t actually about sex.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frkrg"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhy do we have sex then? To procreate, sure. To bond, fine. But those are just two of many possible answers. Like many cultural phenomena, sex exceeds its why. Think of food. From a survival standpoint, it makes sense that we eat, and that we eat together &ndash; after all, it was advantageous to our ancestors to pool their resources (more for our group means more for \u003Cem\u003Eme\u003C\u002Fem\u003E). But when we move from those things to contemporary culinary culture &ndash; burgers topped with gold shavings, Instagram food accounts, the cooking network, happy hours with colleagues, after church potluck dinners &ndash; it becomes harder and harder to nail down the exact purpose of our relationship to food. The difference between us and many non-human animals is that we regularly take pleasure in doing useless things. We do them, that is, because we enjoy them, because participating in such activities brings us pleasure &mdash; the kind that distracts us from any \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E questions. It&rsquo;s possible, writes Halperin, that &ldquo;the act of sex makes sense only when it makes no sense.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20170315-the-invention-of-heterosexuality\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EThe invention of heterosexuality\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160627-i-am-gay-but-i-wasnt-born-this-way\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E&ldquo;I am gay &ndash; but I wasn&rsquo;t born this way&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fculture\u002Fstory\u002F20190618-how-pop-culture-embraced-sexuality-without-labels\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EHow pop culture embraced sexuality &ldquo;without labels&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerhaps it&rsquo;s time to admit that enjoyment is the main reason most of us &mdash;&nbsp;including the most pious among us &mdash;&nbsp;have sex.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo be fair, there&rsquo;s usually a point to having sex, otherwise we&rsquo;d be doing something else. But the last few decades have seen us challenging the ideas that sex should only be had \u003Cem\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fem\u003E specific purposes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pill was revolutionary on this front, giving some people plenty to fear. In a 1968 Readers Digest article, author \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pbs.org\u002Fwgbh\u002Famericanexperience\u002Ffeatures\u002Fpill-and-sexual-revolution\u002F\"\u003EPearl Buck said\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \"Everyone knows what the pill is. It is a small object &ndash; yet its potential effect upon our society many be even more devastating than the nuclear bomb.\" Like a good many conservatives&rsquo; ideas, Buck&rsquo;s argument seemed to be informed by a hysteria that sex without \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E would spell the end of civilisation. For these folks, the so-called sexual revolution was to blame for modern relaxed views on sex practices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frj96"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile the sexual revolution is often used as a bogeyman to end rather than contribute to important conversations, sweeping changes in public perceptions of sex beginning in the 60s have been noted by researchers. In a 2015 \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flink-springer-com.ezp1.villanova.edu\u002Fcontent\u002Fpdf\u002F10.1007\u002Fs10508-015-0540-2.pdf\"\u003Eresearch paper\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, Jean M Twenge, a psychology professor at San Diego State University, examined American attitudes toward sex from the 1970s to 2010s. Her conclusion: &ldquo;Between the 1970s and the 2010s, Americans became more accepting of non-marital sex.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsistent with past research finding declines in religious orientation and increases in individualistic traits, more Americans believe that sexuality need not be restricted by social conventions. Recent generations are also acting on this belief, reporting a significantly higher number of sexual partners as adults and more having casual sex than those born earlier in the 20th Century.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwenge points out that within a population, attitudes may still vary for many reasons (depending on age, race, sex, religious beliefs etc), but research shows that &ldquo;meaningful generational changes in sexual attitudes and behavior have occurred&rdquo; over time.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOur views on sex, then, are very much the product of our location in a particular time and place. Our sexual ethics aren&rsquo;t timeless: they evolved, and they will continue to evolve. Perhaps much more quickly than we are prepared for.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhat's natural?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELike every human phenomenon, sexual activity came from somewhere. It isn&rsquo;t just here. We&rsquo;ve arrived at our sex practices and attitudes and ethics via a long and winding journey from animals that predate us, a journey that goes back to the earliest life in the universe.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut even if we concentrate on our species, we find plenty of evidence that some traditional ideas about sex are less natural than we thought. I once heard an American Evangelical preacher condemn homosexuality with what to his congregation seemed to be a funny joke. &ldquo;I shouldn&rsquo;t have to remind you that two men aren&rsquo;t supposed to be together. Even barnyard animals know that!&rdquo; What the pastor was arguing was that homosexuality is unnatural, which is why animals don&rsquo;t practise it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExcept they do. Japanese macaques, fruit flies, flour beetles, albatrosses, bottlenose dolphins &ndash; these are just some of the more than 500 species in which homosexuality is observed, as \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fearth\u002Fstory\u002F20150206-are-there-any-homosexual-animals\"\u003EMelissa Hogenboom\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has written for BBC.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The meaning of heterosexual sex has been constructed in opposition of homosexual sex","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETo be sure, animals don&rsquo;t identify as gay, but neither do they identify as not gay. Which brings us to the extremely obvious but rarely contemplated fact &ndash; that humans have, at least for the last century, defined themselves based on the kind of sex they have. Heterosexual sex has come to mean something; specifically, its meaning has been constructed in opposition to homosexual sex. If you want to understand what that meaning is, then you might start by asking yourself a question Jonathan Ned Katz poses in \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fieas.unideb.hu\u002Fadmin\u002Ffile_9700.pdf\"\u003EThe Invention of Heterosexuality\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;Whose interests have been served by the division of the world into heterosexual and homosexual?&rdquo; Any child who was teased, as I was, for appearing gay knows that distinction was not made with their best interests in mind.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat&rsquo;s interesting is to think about how long the hetero\u002Fhomo line will continue to hold. A 2019 YouGov \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftoday.yougov.com\u002Ftopics\u002Flifestyle\u002Farticles-reports\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F20\u002Fkinsey-scale-sexuality-millennials-2019-poll\"\u003Esurvey\u003C\u002Fa\u003E found that nearly four in 10 millennials don&rsquo;t identify as &ldquo;completely heterosexual.&rdquo; That probably says less about changing sexual orientations than it does about the changing meaning of those orientations. Simply put, it is probably less important today than it was three decades ago to define one&rsquo;s identity based on sexual activity. In a world where same-sex orientation and activity is largely accepted to be a healthy and natural variety of human sexuality, it is no longer very important to form a public identity based on sexual practices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerhaps the more we divorce sex from its \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, the less people will think about what sex acts might mean and how those might contribute to an individual&rsquo;s identity.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frl5p"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe question of the purpose of sex is not the stumbling block to gay culture that it is to straight culture. Some of that is situational: without the prospect of biological pregnancies and (until recently) marriage to tie them down, gay people are free to have sex for the sole purpose of having sex.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI don&rsquo;t mean to suggest that gay sex doesn&rsquo;t have a \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E: it can have many \u003Cem\u003Ewhys\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, including, of course, love. But gay culture has, historically, been more open to the idea that it might not always have a \u003Cem\u003Ewhy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, and that it doesn&rsquo;t always need to. That, of course, might seem to buck those long-held and cherished cultural ideas and ethics about sex, which could perhaps explain the historic prejudice against gay people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELike many children, I was taught to adjudicate the ethics of a sexual encounter based solely on whether or not it happened in a committed, monogamous relationship (usually marriage). But eventually, I started questioning this standard &ndash; particularly because the same people who taught it to me also taught me that humans were created by God a few thousand years ago. If their biology was so bad, then why pay them any mind on sex, which is a biological phenomenon?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI realised that theirs was not a helpful ethical scheme for gay people who are not able to conceive children through a sexual union. It seemed disingenuous at best, and cruel at worst, to advocate for a sexual standard that prevents a sizeable population of human beings from ever reaching it. Most acts of heterosexual sex do not result in a live birth, and yet for some reason that non-procreative sex is never condemned as unnatural, the way non-procreative homosexual sex has often been condemned.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThankfully, opposition to homosexuality largely continues to decline. A \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwilliamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002FPolarized-Progress-April-2018.pdf\"\u003Estudy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E conducted by the Williams Institute at UCLA School of Law looked at the changing attitudes of people across 141 countries. Eighty, or 57%, of those countries saw an increase in acceptance of LGBT people between the years of 1981 and 2014. It&rsquo;s not all good news: while the researchers found that the traditionally accepting countries (Iceland, Netherlands, Sweden, Denmark, Andorra, and Norway) have become more tolerant over time, the less accepting countries (Azerbaijan, Bangladesh, Georgia, Ghana) have become even less tolerant. While consistent anti-gay attitudes shouldn&rsquo;t be overlooked, it&rsquo;s important to remember that the majority of the countries studied show an increased tolerance for homosexuality.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frp5v"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are many reasons for widespread acceptance of homosexuality, including positive media portrayals of LGBT people, public support of medical and psychological organisations, and the fact that most people personally know LGBT people. (It&rsquo;s harder to believe that gay people want to destroy civilisation when we&rsquo;re your piano teacher or florist or chaplain or local firefighter.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGranted, gay people &ndash; and I&rsquo;ll focus on men here, since that&rsquo;s what I&rsquo;m most familiar with &ndash; aren&rsquo;t always pristine examples of a finely-tuned sex ethic. Gay male communities continue to worship specific body types (muscular, lean, for example), which sends the message that those who don&rsquo;t live up to those aesthetic standards (most of us) are less deserving or worthy than those who do. These exclusive standards have only become more ubiquitous thanks to technologies like Grindr, where men are reduced to pictures of their body parts, and the undesirable are quickly blocked. &ldquo;No fats and fems&rdquo; is, to our shame, an oft-heard refrain on these gay hook-up apps, which means we still have a lot of thinking to do when it comes to our sexual ethics.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut despite these shortcomings, it&rsquo;s gay culture that has all this time been offering the world new ways to think about sexual ethics &ndash;&nbsp;ways that don&rsquo;t involve procreation or marriage or love or even committed, monogamous relationships. Just consider \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Flifeandstyle\u002F2016\u002Fjul\u002F22\u002Fgay-dating-open-relationships-work-study\"\u003Eone 2005 survey\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, which found 40% of gay couples endorse open relationships compared to 5% of straight couples. If these kinds of sexual experiences really do become the norm &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20181211-online-dating-to-polyamory-the-truth-about-relationships\"\u003Eas some suggest\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; it will have been gay people who opened that door.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI suppose some heterosexuals may take umbrage at these ideas, but it&rsquo;s difficult to pretend that straight culture has the moral high ground on sexual issues. As I have \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20170315-the-invention-of-heterosexuality\"\u003Epreviously written\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, popular culture in 2019 is replete with cases of dysfunctional straight relationships, affairs and marriages. The &ldquo;traditional&rdquo; heterosexual sexual ethic &ndash; which was, as historians have long held, invented in the 19th Century &ndash; has been tried and found wanting.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frlw8"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOver the years, various futurists have been predicting what the future of sex will be like. From virtual porn and human augmentation to remote hookups (where people, at a distance, bring each other to orgasm via haptic technologies), the future of sex will be more digital, more synthetic, less organic, less messy.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut while the future will no doubt bring with it major technological changes, we should also consider that some of the biggest changes in the future will involve new ideas.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere will be new ideas about procreation. Since 1978, more than eight million babies have been born through IVF. That number is set to drastically rise the more ubiquitous and affordable the technologies become. Birth control and contraception have also helped separate sex and procreation in our cultural imagination. If Greely&rsquo;s predictions about PGD are right, then at some point within the next four decades, there will be a sea change when it comes to how babies are born. PGD will become &ldquo;easy&rdquo; (accessible and affordable) thanks to developments in genetics and stem cell research. Here&rsquo;s how \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fcommentisfree\u002F2016\u002Fapr\u002F01\u002Fsex-babies-humans-parents-technology-science-fiction-pgd\"\u003EGreely sums up the research in The Guardian\u003C\u002Fa\u003E:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\"A couple who wants children will visit a clinic &ndash; he will leave a sperm sample; she will leave a skin sample. A week or two later, the prospective parents will receive information on 100 embryos created from their cells, telling them what the embryos&rsquo; genomes predict about their future&hellip; Then they will select which embryos to move into the womb for possible pregnancy and birth.\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeople might bristle at the thought of &ldquo;designer babies,&rdquo; but when we remember that most people who have babies \u003Cem\u003Eselect\u003C\u002Fem\u003E each other based on traits, knowing full well that such traits will likely be passed onto their offspring, it gets harder to draw a line between the technologies that Greely writes about and run-of-the-mill reproduction-via-sex. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere will be new ideas about monogamy and commitment. Having one sexual partner for one&rsquo;s entire adult life seems like a more easily achieved prospect when life expectancy is lower. But \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdata.worldbank.org\u002Findicator\u002Fsp.dyn.le00.in\"\u003Elife expectancy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for humans has been on the rise. From 1960 to 2017, the average increased by 20 years. By 2040, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.usnews.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld\u002Farticles\u002F2018-10-16\u002Fstudy-global-lifespan-to-increase-by-2040\"\u003Eestimates\u003C\u002Fa\u003E claim life expectancy will be up more than four years. That&rsquo;s a conservative number to some futurists. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Fnews\u002Fscientists-up-stakes-in-bet-on-whether-humans-will-live-to-150-1.20818\"\u003ESteven Austad\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, for instance, believes the first human to live to 150 years old was born before 2001. How realistic is it to require someone to limit his- or herself to the same one sex partner for 130 years? But we needn&rsquo;t look that far ahead. Even now, divorce and remarriage rates continue to climb. According to a 2013 \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pewresearch.org\u002Ffact-tank\u002F2019\u002F02\u002F13\u002F8-facts-about-love-and-marriage\u002F\"\u003EPew survey\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, four in 10 American marriages involve the remarriage of at least one of the couple. Perhaps, with longer life expectancies, &ldquo;till death do us part&rdquo; will simply cease to be our aim.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07frm3d"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190702-are-we-set-for-a-new-sexual-revolution-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere will be new ideas about sexual identity. If sex ceases to mean anything other than sex; if children are not teased for having a &ldquo;different&rdquo; sexual orientation; if procreation happens in a lab; might future humans feel free to have sex with men and women at will? Or might they feel comfortable cultivating their own sexual desires? Is the concept of sexual orientation and identity tied to an archaic notion of reproduction? In the future, will words like &ldquo;heterosexual&rdquo; and &ldquo;homosexual&rdquo; be heard only in the history classroom?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese ideas will continue to become even more mainstream &mdash; thanks, in no small part, to the many LGBT people who have, for the past few decades, been inviting the dominant culture to rethink its sexual ethics.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA few years ago at a conference, I heard the philosopher and gender-theorist Judith Butler say, &ldquo;Maybe the truly queer thing to do with sex is to just enjoy it.&rdquo; I didn&rsquo;t agree at the time, but I now realise she was onto something.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerhaps sex will always be \u003Cem\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fem\u003E something &ndash; but it will be for a whom, not a what. It will be for us, the people who have it, who enjoy it. The meaning of sex won&rsquo;t exist apart from the compassion and enjoyment it brings people &ndash; the enjoyment of physical sensation, of social bonding, of experimenting.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the future, the meaning of sex will be sex.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBrandon Ambrosino has written for the New York Times, Boston Globe, The Atlantic, Politico, Economist, and other publications. He lives in Delaware. \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin more than one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E or \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\